            "content": "# Todo App — Build Plan\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThis is not just another todo list. It's a fast, resilient personal task manager that works seamlessly whether you're online or offline. Built with a React + Vite frontend and a FastAPI + SQLite backend, the app gives users a fluid, tactile experience for capturing, organizing, and completing tasks. Drag-and-drop reordering, inline editing, and instant optimistic updates make the interface feel native — not like a web page pretending to be an app.\n\nThe offline-first architecture is the app's defining quality. Users can create, edit, reorder, and delete tasks with zero network connectivity. When the connection returns, a conflict-aware sync engine reconciles local and remote state automatically. SQLite on the backend keeps deployment simple — a single binary and a single file — while IndexedDB on the client mirrors the full task store locally. The result is an app that is always available, always responsive, and never loses your work.\n\nBeyond the basics, the app adds thoughtful polish: keyboard shortcuts for power users, smooth animations on reorder, a dark/light theme that respects system preferences, and a clean, opinionated visual design that makes the mundane act of managing tasks feel surprisingly satisfying.\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────┐\n│           React + Vite SPA          │\n│  ┌───────────┐  ┌────────────────┐  │\n│  │ Task Store │  │  Sync Engine   │  │\n│  │ (Zustand)  │──│ (ServiceWorker)│  │\n│  └─────┬─────┘  └───────┬────────┘  │\n│        │                │           │\n│  ┌─────▼─────┐  ┌───────▼────────┐  │\n│  │  IndexedDB │  │  Offline Queue │  │\n│  │  (Dexie)   │  │  (Dexie table) │  │\n│  └────────────┘  └────────────────┘  │\n└──────────────────┬──────────────────┘\n                   │ REST + JSON\n┌──────────────────▼──────────────────┐\n│          FastAPI Backend            │\n│  ┌────────────┐  ┌───────────────┐  │\n│  │  Routers   │  │  Pydantic     │  │\n│  │  /api/v1/* │  │  Models       │  │\n│  └─────┬──────┘  └───────────────┘  │\n│  ┌─────▼──────┐  ┌───────────────┐  │\n│  │  Service   │  │  Sync Service │  │\n│  │  Layer     │  │  (CRDT-lite)  │  │\n│  └─────┬──────┘  └───────────────┘  │\n│  ┌─────▼──────┐                     │\n│  │  SQLite    │                     │\n│  │  (aiosqlite)│                    │\n│  └────────────┘                     │\n└─────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n**Frontend:** React 18+ with TypeScript, Vite for bundling, Zustand for state management, Dexie.js for IndexedDB access, dnd-kit for drag-and-drop, Framer Motion for animations. A service worker handles offline caching and background sync.\n\n**Backend:** FastAPI with Python 3.12+, aiosqlite for async SQLite access, Pydantic v2 for validation. The API follows RESTful conventions with a `/api/v1/` prefix. A lightweight sync protocol uses vector timestamps per-item to resolve conflicts on reconnect.\n\n**Data Model:** Each todo item carries an `id` (UUID), `title`, `description`, `completed` (bool), `position` (float for fractional indexing), `created_at`, `updated_at`, and a `version` counter for conflict detection.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 1: Project Skeleton & Core Backend\n\n### Scope\n- Initialize the monorepo structure with frontend and backend directories\n- Set up Vite + React + TypeScript with strict tsconfig\n- Set up FastAPI with project structure (routers, models, services, database)\n- Create the SQLite schema and database initialization\n- Implement CRUD API endpoints for todo items\n- Add comprehensive input validation with Pydantic\n- Write backend tests with pytest\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/` — Vite + React + TS scaffold with a running dev server\n- `backend/` — FastAPI app with `main.py`, `routers/todos.py`, `models/todo.py`, `services/todo_service.py`, `database.py`\n- `backend/tests/` — pytest test suite for all CRUD operations\n- `backend/requirements.txt` and `frontend/package.json`\n- SQLite database auto-created on first run\n- API docs available at `/docs` (Swagger UI)\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `npm run dev` starts the frontend on port 5173 without errors\n- `uvicorn backend.main:app` starts the backend on port 8000 without errors\n- `POST /api/v1/todos` with `{\"title\": \"Buy milk\"}` returns 201 with a UUID `id` field\n- `GET /api/v1/todos` returns a JSON array of all todos\n- `GET /api/v1/todos/{id}` returns a single todo with fields: id, title, description, completed, position, created_at, updated_at\n- `PUT /api/v1/todos/{id}` with `{\"title\": \"Buy oat milk\"}` returns 200 with the updated todo\n- `DELETE /api/v1/todos/{id}` returns 204 and subsequent GET returns 404\n- `POST /api/v1/todos` with empty title returns 422 with validation error\n- `GET /api/v1/todos/nonexistent-uuid` returns 404\n- pytest passes with 80%+ coverage on backend code\n- TypeScript compiles with zero errors in strict mode\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use fractional indexing for `position` (e.g., first item = 1.0, inserting between 1.0 and 2.0 = 1.5) to enable efficient reordering without updating every row\n- Use UUIDs (uuid7 preferred) as primary keys to support offline ID generation later\n- Structure FastAPI with dependency injection for the database session\n- Use `aiosqlite` with async context managers for all database access\n- Keep the service layer pure — no FastAPI dependencies in service functions\n- CORS middleware must allow the frontend origin\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 2: Core Frontend — Task List & CRUD UI\n\n### Scope\n- Build the main task list view with a clean, modern design\n- Implement add task form with inline input\n- Implement task completion toggle with checkbox\n- Implement inline task editing (click to edit title)\n- Implement task deletion with confirmation\n- Connect frontend to backend API with a typed API client\n- Add loading and error states\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/api/todoClient.ts` — typed fetch wrapper for all endpoints\n- `frontend/src/store/todoStore.ts` — Zustand store with all CRUD actions\n- `frontend/src/components/TaskList.tsx` — main list component\n- `frontend/src/components/TaskItem.tsx` — individual task row\n- `frontend/src/components/AddTaskInput.tsx` — inline task creation\n- `frontend/src/components/EmptyState.tsx` — shown when no tasks exist\n- CSS/styling files with a polished visual design\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User sees an empty state message when no tasks exist\n- User can type a task title and press Enter to add it; the task appears in the list immediately\n- User can click a checkbox to toggle task completion; completed tasks show strikethrough styling\n- User can double-click a task title to enter edit mode, change the text, and press Enter to save\n- User can press Escape while editing to cancel without saving changes\n- User can click a delete button on a task; the task is removed from the list\n- All operations persist to the backend (page refresh preserves state)\n- Loading spinner appears while initial data is being fetched\n- Error toast/banner appears if the backend is unreachable\n- The UI is visually polished — proper spacing, typography, and color palette (not default browser styles)\n- Adding a task with an empty title shows a validation message\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use Zustand with immer middleware for ergonomic immutable updates\n- Implement optimistic updates: update the UI immediately, then sync to the backend; roll back on failure\n- Use a debounced save for inline editing (300ms after last keystroke)\n- Design for keyboard-first interaction: Tab to navigate, Enter to confirm, Escape to cancel\n- Keep components small and focused — each component under 150 lines\n- Use CSS Modules or a utility-first approach (e.g., Tailwind) for styling\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 3: Drag-and-Drop Reordering\n\n### Scope\n- Add drag-and-drop reordering to the task list\n- Implement smooth animations during drag operations\n- Persist new order to the backend\n- Add keyboard-accessible reordering (Alt+Up/Down)\n- Visual feedback during drag (placeholder, shadow, scale)\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/SortableTaskList.tsx` — dnd-kit powered sortable list\n- `frontend/src/components/DragHandle.tsx` — visible drag affordance\n- Backend `PATCH /api/v1/todos/reorder` endpoint accepting an ordered list of IDs\n- Updated Zustand store with reorder action\n- Animation styles for drag interactions\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can drag a task by its drag handle and drop it at a new position; the list reorders smoothly\n- A visual placeholder shows where the item will be dropped during drag\n- The dragged item has a subtle shadow/scale effect while being dragged\n- After dropping, the new order persists across page refresh\n- User can press Alt+ArrowUp or Alt+ArrowDown to move a focused task up or down\n- Keyboard reordering also persists to the backend\n- Reordering 20+ items performs without visible lag or jank\n- The drag handle has a visible grip icon and changes cursor to `grab`/`grabbing`\n- Touch devices can long-press to initiate drag (mobile-friendly)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `@dnd-kit/core` and `@dnd-kit/sortable` for the drag-and-drop implementation\n- Use Framer Motion's `AnimatePresence` and `layout` prop for smooth reorder animations\n- On drop, compute new fractional position between neighbors rather than rewriting all positions\n- The `PATCH /api/v1/todos/reorder` endpoint should accept `{ items: [{ id, position }] }` to batch-update positions\n- Debounce the reorder API call (500ms) to batch rapid keyboard reordering\n- Use `touch-action: none` on drag handles for mobile compatibility\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 4: Task Details & Rich Features\n\n### Scope\n- Add an expandable detail panel for each task\n- Support task descriptions (multi-line text)\n- Add due dates with a date picker\n- Add priority levels (none, low, medium, high) with color coding\n- Add filter/sort controls (by status, priority, due date)\n- Add task count summary in header\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/TaskDetail.tsx` — expandable detail panel\n- `frontend/src/components/DatePicker.tsx` — lightweight date picker component\n- `frontend/src/components/PriorityBadge.tsx` — colored priority indicator\n- `frontend/src/components/FilterBar.tsx` — filter and sort controls\n- `frontend/src/components/TaskSummary.tsx` — header with counts\n- Updated backend models and migration to add `description`, `due_date`, `priority` fields\n- Updated API endpoints to accept and return new fields\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can click a task to expand its detail panel showing description, due date, and priority\n- User can add/edit a multi-line description in the detail panel\n- User can set a due date using a date picker; overdue tasks show a red indicator\n- User can set priority (none/low/medium/high); each level has a distinct color\n- User can filter tasks by: all, active, completed\n- User can sort tasks by: manual order, due date, priority, created date\n- Task summary header shows \"3 of 7 tasks completed\" style count\n- Filters and sort persist across page navigation (stored in URL query params)\n- Backend validates that due_date is a valid ISO date and priority is one of the allowed values\n- All new fields are optional — existing tasks without them still display correctly\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use a slide-down animation for the detail panel expansion\n- Store filter/sort state in URL search params for shareability and back-button support\n- Add database migration logic — check for column existence before ALTER TABLE\n- Priority should be stored as an integer (0-3) in the database, mapped to labels in the frontend\n- Date picker should support keyboard input as well as click selection\n- Use `Intl.RelativeTimeFormat` for relative due date display (\"due tomorrow\", \"overdue by 3 days\")\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 5: Offline Storage & Service Worker\n\n### Scope\n- Set up IndexedDB with Dexie.js to mirror the full task store locally\n- Install and configure a service worker for offline asset caching\n- Make all CRUD operations work entirely offline against IndexedDB\n- Add online/offline status indicator in the UI\n- Queue mutations made while offline for later sync\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/db/localDb.ts` — Dexie database definition\n- `frontend/src/db/offlineQueue.ts` — mutation queue stored in IndexedDB\n- `frontend/src/sw.ts` — service worker with asset precaching and runtime caching\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useOnlineStatus.ts` — reactive online/offline hook\n- `frontend/src/components/OfflineIndicator.tsx` — banner/badge showing connectivity status\n- Vite PWA plugin configuration (`vite.config.ts`)\n- Updated Zustand store to read/write from IndexedDB when offline\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- After first load, the app opens and displays tasks even with no network (airplane mode)\n- User can add, edit, complete, delete, and reorder tasks while offline; all changes persist in IndexedDB\n- A subtle offline indicator appears when the app detects no connectivity\n- The indicator changes to \"syncing...\" when connectivity is restored\n- Refreshing the page while offline still shows all tasks\n- The service worker caches all static assets (JS, CSS, HTML, fonts)\n- Chrome DevTools > Application > Service Workers shows the SW as active\n- Chrome DevTools > Application > IndexedDB shows the local task database with data\n- Tasks created offline have valid UUIDs (not server-generated)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `vite-plugin-pwa` with `injectManifest` strategy for maximum control over the service worker\n- Dexie.js tables: `todos` (mirrors server schema), `syncQueue` (pending mutations with timestamp and operation type)\n- The sync queue should store operations as `{ id, operation: 'create'|'update'|'delete', payload, timestamp }`\n- Generate UUIDs on the client side (use `crypto.randomUUID()`) so offline-created tasks have stable IDs\n- The Zustand store should use a \"local-first\" pattern: always write to IndexedDB first, then enqueue a sync operation\n- Use the `navigator.onLine` API plus a periodic fetch heartbeat for reliable online detection\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 6: Sync Engine & Conflict Resolution\n\n### Scope\n- Build a background sync engine that replays queued mutations when online\n- Implement conflict detection using version counters\n- Build a conflict resolution UI for manual resolution when needed\n- Add a sync status indicator per task\n- Handle edge cases: duplicate creates, stale deletes, concurrent edits\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncEngine.ts` — background sync orchestrator\n- `frontend/src/sync/conflictResolver.ts` — conflict detection and auto-resolution logic\n- `frontend/src/components/ConflictDialog.tsx` — UI for manual conflict resolution\n- `frontend/src/components/SyncStatus.tsx` — per-task sync indicator (synced/pending/conflict)\n- Backend `POST /api/v1/todos/sync` endpoint accepting batch mutations with version checks\n- Backend conflict detection returning `409 Conflict` with server version when mismatch detected\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Tasks created offline sync to the server automatically when connectivity returns\n- Tasks edited offline sync without user intervention if no conflict exists\n- Tasks deleted offline are deleted on the server upon sync\n- If a task was edited both offline and on the server, a conflict dialog appears showing both versions\n- User can choose \"keep mine\", \"keep server\", or \"merge\" in the conflict dialog\n- After resolving all conflicts, the sync status shows all tasks as \"synced\"\n- A small icon on each task indicates its sync status: checkmark (synced), clock (pending), warning (conflict)\n- Rapid toggling of online/offline does not produce duplicate tasks\n- The sync queue is cleared only after successful server acknowledgment\n- Backend returns `409` when `PUT /api/v1/todos/{id}` receives a stale `version` value\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use an exponential backoff retry strategy for failed sync attempts (1s, 2s, 4s, max 30s)\n- Process the sync queue in order (FIFO) to preserve causality\n- The batch sync endpoint should be transactional — all succeed or all fail, with per-item error reporting\n- For auto-resolution: if only non-overlapping fields changed, merge automatically; if the same field changed, prompt the user\n- Version counters increment on every successful write; the server rejects writes with `version < current_version`\n- Use a Web Worker or `requestIdleCallback` for sync processing to avoid blocking the UI thread\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 7: Visual Polish, Animations & Theming\n\n### Scope\n- Implement dark/light theme with system preference detection\n- Add smooth animations for all state transitions (add, remove, complete, reorder)\n- Refine typography, spacing, and visual hierarchy\n- Add micro-interactions (hover states, focus rings, button feedback)\n- Implement responsive design for mobile, tablet, and desktop\n- Add keyboard shortcut overlay (press `?` to show)\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/theme/` — theme tokens, CSS custom properties, theme toggle component\n- `frontend/src/components/ThemeToggle.tsx` — dark/light/system mode switcher\n- `frontend/src/components/KeyboardShortcuts.tsx` — shortcut help overlay\n- Updated component styles with animations and transitions\n- Responsive layout breakpoints and mobile-optimized touch targets\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useKeyboardShortcuts.ts` — global keyboard shortcut handler\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- The app respects `prefers-color-scheme` on first load (dark or light)\n- User can toggle between dark, light, and system theme; preference persists across sessions\n- Adding a task animates it sliding in from the top\n- Completing a task shows a satisfying checkmark animation before applying strikethrough\n- Deleting a task animates it sliding out with a fade\n- Reordering shows smooth position transitions (no teleporting)\n- On mobile (< 640px), the layout is single-column with appropriately sized touch targets (min 44px)\n- Pressing `?` shows a keyboard shortcuts overlay listing all available shortcuts\n- Pressing `n` focuses the new task input\n- Pressing `j`/`k` navigates up/down the task list\n- Focus rings are visible on keyboard navigation but hidden on mouse interaction\n- All interactive elements have hover and active states\n- Color contrast meets WCAG AA standards in both themes\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use CSS custom properties for theming — swap a class on `<html>` to switch themes\n- Store theme preference in `localStorage`\n- Use `prefers-reduced-motion` media query to disable animations for users who prefer it\n- Use Framer Motion's `layout` animations for reorder transitions\n- Mobile breakpoints: 640px (mobile), 768px (tablet), 1024px (desktop)\n- Use `:focus-visible` for keyboard-only focus rings\n- Test contrast ratios with Chrome DevTools accessibility panel\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 8: Performance, PWA & Production Readiness\n\n### Scope\n- Optimize bundle size with code splitting and tree shaking\n- Add PWA manifest for installability (Add to Home Screen)\n- Implement virtual scrolling for large task lists (1000+ items)\n- Add comprehensive error boundaries\n- Add end-to-end tests for critical flows\n- Performance audit and optimization pass\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/public/manifest.json` — PWA web app manifest with icons\n- `frontend/src/components/VirtualTaskList.tsx` — virtualized list for performance\n- `frontend/src/components/ErrorBoundary.tsx` — React error boundary with recovery UI\n- `frontend/e2e/` — Playwright end-to-end test suite\n- `backend/tests/test_sync.py` — sync endpoint integration tests\n- Performance optimization: lazy loading, memoization, bundle analysis\n- PWA icons in multiple sizes (192x192, 512x512)\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Lighthouse PWA score is 90+\n- Lighthouse Performance score is 90+ on mobile\n- The app is installable via \"Add to Home Screen\" on Chrome and Safari\n- A list of 1000 tasks scrolls at 60fps without dropped frames\n- The initial JS bundle is under 200KB gzipped\n- React error boundary catches component errors and shows a \"Something went wrong\" screen with a retry button\n- Playwright tests cover: add task, complete task, delete task, reorder task, offline mode, sync\n- All Playwright tests pass in CI-like headless mode\n- Backend response time for `GET /api/v1/todos` with 1000 items is under 100ms\n- No console errors or warnings in production build\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `React.lazy` and `Suspense` for code splitting the detail panel and conflict dialog\n- Use `@tanstack/react-virtual` for virtual scrolling\n- PWA manifest needs `display: \"standalone\"`, appropriate theme colors, and at least two icon sizes\n- Run `npx vite-bundle-visualizer` and eliminate any unexpected large dependencies\n- Use `React.memo` on `TaskItem` to prevent unnecessary re-renders during list operations\n- E2E tests should use a separate test database and test server\n- Add `Cache-Control` headers for API responses where appropriate\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 9: Search, Bulk Actions & Undo\n\n### Scope\n- Add instant search/filter across all tasks\n- Implement bulk selection with select-all and multi-select\n- Add bulk actions: complete all, delete selected, change priority\n- Implement undo/redo for all destructive actions\n- Add toast notifications for action feedback\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/SearchBar.tsx` — instant search with highlight\n- `frontend/src/components/BulkActions.tsx` — toolbar for bulk operations\n- `frontend/src/store/undoStore.ts` — undo/redo history stack\n- `frontend/src/components/Toast.tsx` — toast notification system\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useUndoRedo.ts` — undo/redo hook with Ctrl+Z/Ctrl+Shift+Z\n- Updated backend endpoints for bulk operations\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n-