oject.toml.example    # Template for new projects\n└── README.md\n```\n\n**Per-project workspace** (created at runtime):\n```\nworkspace/<project-name>/\n├── project.toml                # User-defined: name, goals, thresholds, budgets\n├── state.json                  # Machine-managed run state\n├── plan.md                     # Planner output\n├── costs.json                  # Running cost tally\n├── mjolnir.log                   # Append-only structured JSONL log\n└── sprints/\n    ├── 01/\n    │   ├── contract.md         # Sprint contract (from plan)\n    │   └── eval_report.json    # Evaluator scores + feedback\n    └── 02/ ...\n```\n\n## Implementation Steps\n\n### Step 1: Project scaffold + config system\n- Create `forge/` directory structure\n- Write `project.toml.example` with fields: name, description, goals, tech_stack, thresholds (design_quality=7, originality=5, craft=6, functionality=6), weights (0.35, 0.25, 0.25, 0.15), budget_per_sprint, max_retries\n- Write `lib/state.py` — atomic JSON state read/write with `tmp + mv` pattern\n- Write `lib/notify.py` — ntfy.sh sender (single POST, non-fatal on failure)\n\n### Step 2: Stream parser\n- Write `lib/parse_stream.py` — reads JSONL from stdin, emits structured events\n- Must detect: `rate_limit_event` (extract `resetsAt`), `result` (extract cost, error status), `assistant` messages\n- Returns structured dict: `{output, cost, rate_limited, resets_at, error}`\n\n### Step 3: Orchestrator core (forge.sh)\n- `run_agent()` function: invokes `claude -p --output-format stream-json --verbose --permission-mode bypassPermissions` with system prompt file, pipes through `parse_stream.py`\n- Rate limit handling: on `rate_limit_event`, save state, compute wait time from `resetsAt`, sleep, resume\n- State transitions: atomic writes to `state.json` before each phase\n- Main loop: `planning → (generating → evaluating → threshold check → pass/retry) → complete`\n- Max retries per sprint (default 3), halt on exhaustion\n\n### Step 4: Prompt engineering\n- **planner.md**: Takes project.toml, outputs plan.md with numbered sprints, each with a sprint contract (scope, deliverables, acceptance criteria). Instructed to be ambitious.\n- **generator.md**: Reads plan + sprint contract + previous eval feedback. Knows it will be evaluated on design quality and originality (weighted higher). Writes complete, runnable code. Commits per logical unit.\n- **evaluator.md**: Strict QA agent. Scores 1-10 on four criteria with justifications. **Uses Playwright CLI (`npx playwright`) to interact with live UI** — takes screenshots, clicks elements, fills forms, navigates pages before scoring. Hard thresholds — below any threshold = sprint fails. Calibrated with few-shot examples at different quality levels. Outputs `eval_report.json`.\n- **rubric.md**: Shared rubric with detailed score descriptions (9-10, 7-8, 5-6, 3-4, 1-2) for each criterion.\n\n### Step 5: Monitoring and steering\n- **ntfy.sh integration**: Notifications on sprint start, pass, fail, rate limit, error, completion. Mobile app shows push notifications.\n- **forge.log**: Append-only JSONL — every event timestamped. Tail via SSH.\n- **state.json**: Single source of truth. Read via SSH for current status.\n- **Steering**: Edit `state.json` via SSH to pause (set phase=halted), skip sprint, adjust attempt count, then restart tmux session.\n- Optional: `nc` one-liner status endpoint on port 8080 for quick phone browser check.\n\n### Step 6: Crash recovery and watchdog\n- **forge-watchdog.sh**: Cron job (every 5 min). Checks if tmux session `mjolnir` is alive. If dead and state is non-terminal, restarts. Respects rate_limit_until (won't restart if still waiting).\n- **install.sh**: Installs cron watchdog, verifies deps (claude CLI, python3, tmux, jq), sets up tmux session template.\n\n### Step 7: Testing and hardening\n- Test with a simple project (e.g., \"build a CLI calculator in Python\")\n- Verify: rate limit recovery (simulate by lowering budget), crash recovery (kill tmux mid-sprint), state resume, notification delivery\n- Test on Raspberry Pi (ARM compatibility)\n\n## Evaluation Scoring Rubric (weights match blog post emphasis)\n\n| Criterion | Weight | Threshold | What it measures |\n|-----------|--------|-----------|-----------------|\n| Design Quality | 0.35 | 7 | Architecture, cohesion, separation of concerns, patterns |\n| Originality | 0.25 | 5 | Creative solutions, non-obvious approaches, beyond boilerplate |\n| Craft | 0.25 | 6 | Code style, naming, consistency, polish, error handling |\n| Functionality | 0.15 | 6 | Correctness, edge cases, usability |\n\nSprint passes only if ALL scores >= their threshold. Weighted score tracked for trend analysis.\n\n## Error Handling State Machine\n\n```\nidle → planning → generating ⇄ evaluating → complete\n                      ↑              │\n                      └── retry ─────┘ (attempt < max)\n                                     │\n                                     └── halted (attempt >= max)\n\nANY state → rate_limited → sleep(resetsAt + 60s) → resume previous state\nANY state → error → auto-retry once → halted (if retry fails)\n```\n\nRecovery mechanisms:\n- **Rate limit**: Parse `resetsAt` from JSONL stream, sleep, resume exact phase\n- **Crash**: `state.json` persists phase. Watchdog cron restarts into same phase.\n- **Manual**: SSH in, edit `state.json`, restart tmux session\n\n## Technology Choices\n\n| Component | Choice | Why |\n|-----------|--------|-----|\n| Orchestrator | Bash | Zero deps, native to CLI, runs on RPi/VPS/Mac |\n| Utilities | Python 3 | JSON/JSONL parsing, notifications. Pre-installed everywhere |\n| Agent invocation | `claude -p --output-format stream-json --verbose` | Headless, streamable, rate limit events visible |\n| Persistence | tmux + cron watchdog | Survives SSH disconnect. Simpler than systemd, works cross-platform |\n| Notifications | ntfy.sh | Free push to iOS/Android. One `curl` call. Self-hostable |\n| Monitoring | SSH + file tail + optional nc endpoint | Zero infrastructure |\n| Inter-agent comms | Files (plan.md, eval_report.json) | Debuggable, matches blog post pattern |\n\n## Verification\n\n1. **Unit test the stream parser**: Feed it sample JSONL with rate_limit_event, verify it extracts resetsAt correctly\n2. **Test state machine**: Write state, kill process, restart, verify it resumes from correct phase\n3. **Dry run**: Run mjolnir with a trivial project.toml (\"build a hello world CLI\"), verify full planner → generator → evaluator cycle completes\n4. **Rate limit test**: Set `--max-budget-usd 0.01` to trigger early budget exhaustion, verify graceful handling\n5. **Crash recovery test**: Kill tmux mid-sprint, verify watchdog restarts and resumes\n6. **Notification test**: Run `python3 lib/notify.py \"test\" \"info\"`, verify push arrives on phone\n7. **RPi test**: SSH to RPi, clone repo, run install.sh, run a full project cycle\n\n## Cost Estimates (per project run)\n\nBased on blog post V2 harness numbers, scaled to this architecture:\n- Planner: ~$0.50 (single invocation)\n- Per sprint: Generator ~$40-80, Evaluator ~$5-10\n- 5-sprint project: ~$225-450 total\n- With Max plan: usage-capped, not billed per token — but rate limits apply (5-hour windows)\n",
