            "content": "# Todo App — Build Plan\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThis is not just another todo app — it's a fast, reliable, offline-first task manager that feels native on the web. Users should be able to capture, organize, and complete tasks with zero friction, whether they're online, offline, or transitioning between states. The app prioritizes speed of interaction: adding a task should feel instant, reordering should be buttery smooth via drag-and-drop, and edits should happen inline without modal interruptions.\n\nThe architecture splits cleanly between a React + TypeScript frontend (bundled with Vite) and a FastAPI + SQLite backend. SQLite gives us a zero-config, file-based database that's perfect for single-user or small-team scenarios, while FastAPI provides async performance and automatic OpenAPI documentation. The offline-first design means the frontend maintains its own local state (via IndexedDB) and syncs with the backend opportunistically — the app is fully functional without a network connection.\n\nBeyond the basics, this app should demonstrate craft: thoughtful animations on reorder, keyboard-driven workflows, clear visual hierarchy, and a design that feels intentional rather than generic. Accessibility, error recovery, and data integrity during sync conflicts are first-class concerns, not afterthoughts.\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                   Frontend                       │\n│  React 18 + TypeScript + Vite                    │\n│                                                  │\n│  ┌───────────┐  ┌────────────┐  ┌─────────────┐ │\n│  │ Components │  │ State Mgmt │  │  Sync Layer │ │\n│  │ (UI)       │  │ (Zustand)  │  │ (Service    │ │\n│  │            │  │            │  │  Worker)    │ │\n│  └───────────┘  └────────────┘  └─────────────┘ │\n│        │              │               │          │\n│        └──────────────┼───────────────┘          │\n│                       │                          │\n│              ┌────────┴────────┐                 │\n│              │   IndexedDB     │                 │\n│              │  (Local Store)  │                 │\n│              └─────────────────┘                 │\n└───────────────────────┬─────────────────────────┘\n                        │ HTTP/REST (when online)\n┌───────────────────────┴─────────────────────────┐\n│                   Backend                        │\n│  FastAPI + Python 3.12+                          │\n│                                                  │\n│  ┌───────────┐  ┌────────────┐  ┌─────────────┐ │\n│  │  Routes   │  │  Services  │  │ Repository  │ │\n│  │ (API)     │  │ (Business) │  │ (Data)      │ │\n│  └───────────┘  └────────────┘  └─────────────┘ │\n│                                       │          │\n│                              ┌────────┴────────┐ │\n│                              │     SQLite      │ │\n│                              │   (Database)    │ │\n│                              └─────────────────┘ │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n**Key architectural decisions:**\n\n- **Zustand** for state management — lightweight, no boilerplate, works well with immutable update patterns\n- **IndexedDB** (via idb library) for offline storage — structured data with indexes, far more capable than localStorage\n- **Service Worker** for offline detection and background sync\n- **Repository pattern** on the backend — SQLite access isolated behind an interface\n- **Optimistic UI** — mutations apply locally first, sync to server in background\n- **Conflict resolution** — last-write-wins with timestamps, with server as source of truth when online\n- **Pydantic models** for request/response validation on the backend\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 1: Project Skeleton & Core Backend API\n\n### Scope\n- Initialize the monorepo structure with frontend and backend directories\n- Set up Vite + React + TypeScript frontend with dev tooling (ESLint, Prettier)\n- Set up FastAPI backend with SQLite database, migrations, and health check\n- Define the Todo data model and implement full CRUD API\n- Configure CORS, environment variables, and dev server proxying\n- Add comprehensive API tests with pytest\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/` — Vite React TypeScript project with `package.json`, `tsconfig.json`, `vite.config.ts`\n- `backend/` — FastAPI project with `pyproject.toml`, `main.py`, `models.py`, `schemas.py`, `repository.py`, `routes/todos.py`\n- `backend/database.py` — SQLite connection management with async support\n- `backend/tests/` — pytest test suite for all CRUD endpoints\n- `README.md` — Setup and run instructions\n- Working `GET /health`, `GET /api/todos`, `POST /api/todos`, `PUT /api/todos/{id}`, `DELETE /api/todos/{id}`, `PATCH /api/todos/{id}/reorder` endpoints\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Running `cd backend && pip install -e . && uvicorn main:app` starts the server on port 8000\n- `GET /health` returns `{\"status\": \"ok\"}` with 200\n- `POST /api/todos` with `{\"title\": \"Buy milk\"}` returns 201 with a JSON body containing `id`, `title`, `completed`, `position`, `created_at`, `updated_at`\n- `GET /api/todos` returns 200 with a JSON array of all todos sorted by `position`\n- `PUT /api/todos/{id}` with `{\"title\": \"Buy oat milk\", \"completed\": true}` returns 200 with the updated todo\n- `DELETE /api/todos/{id}` returns 204 and the todo is no longer returned by GET\n- `PATCH /api/todos/{id}/reorder` with `{\"position\": 2}` updates the todo's position and shifts other todos accordingly\n- Sending invalid data (empty title, non-existent ID) returns appropriate 400/404 errors with descriptive messages\n- `pytest backend/tests/` passes with 80%+ coverage\n- Frontend dev server starts with `cd frontend && npm install && npm run dev`\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `aiosqlite` for async SQLite access in FastAPI\n- Define Pydantic v2 models in `schemas.py` for request/response validation\n- Use a `position` integer field for ordering — when reordering, shift positions of affected items in a single transaction\n- Repository pattern: `TodoRepository` class handles all DB queries, routes call services, services call repository\n- Use `httpx.AsyncClient` with `TestClient` for API tests\n- Frontend is just the Vite scaffold at this point — real UI comes in Sprint 2\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 2: Core Frontend UI & API Integration\n\n### Scope\n- Build the main todo list UI with add, complete, edit, and delete functionality\n- Implement inline editing (click to edit, Enter to save, Escape to cancel)\n- Connect frontend to backend API with a typed API client\n- Add loading states, error handling, and empty states\n- Implement the visual design system (colors, typography, spacing)\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/api/todoApi.ts` — Typed API client with fetch wrapper\n- `frontend/src/store/todoStore.ts` — Zustand store for todo state\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoList.tsx` — Main list container\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — Individual todo item with inline edit\n- `frontend/src/components/AddTodo.tsx` — Input for adding new todos\n- `frontend/src/components/EmptyState.tsx` — Friendly empty state illustration/message\n- `frontend/src/styles/` — CSS modules or Tailwind config for the design system\n- `frontend/src/types/todo.ts` — Shared TypeScript types\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can type a todo title in the input field and press Enter to add it — the todo appears in the list immediately\n- User can click the checkbox next to a todo to toggle its completed state — completed todos show a strikethrough style\n- User can double-click (or click an edit icon) on a todo to enter inline edit mode — the title becomes an editable input\n- Pressing Enter in edit mode saves the change; pressing Escape cancels and reverts\n- User can click a delete button/icon on a todo to remove it — a brief confirmation or undo toast appears\n- When the list is empty, a friendly empty state message is shown (not a blank screen)\n- While data is loading from the API, a skeleton loader or spinner is shown\n- If the API returns an error, a user-friendly error message is displayed (not a raw error)\n- The UI has a clear visual hierarchy: distinct header, input area, and list area\n- All interactive elements have hover/focus states and are keyboard-accessible (Tab, Enter, Escape)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use Zustand with immer middleware for immutable state updates\n- API client should be a thin wrapper around fetch with proper error handling, typed responses, and base URL configuration\n- Consider using `react-hot-toast` or a custom toast component for notifications\n- CSS approach: Tailwind CSS for utility-first styling with a custom color palette\n- All components should be controlled — no uncontrolled form inputs\n- Use `React.memo` on `TodoItem` to prevent unnecessary re-renders in the list\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 3: Drag-and-Drop Reordering\n\n### Scope\n- Implement smooth drag-and-drop reordering of todos\n- Add visual feedback during drag (placeholder, shadow, animation)\n- Persist new order to backend via the reorder API\n- Add keyboard-accessible reordering (Alt+Up/Down)\n- Animate list transitions (add, remove, reorder)\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/DraggableTodoList.tsx` — Drag-and-drop enabled list\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useDragAndDrop.ts` — Custom hook for drag logic (or integration with `@dnd-kit/core`)\n- `frontend/src/components/DragHandle.tsx` — Visual grip handle for dragging\n- Updated `todoStore.ts` with optimistic reorder logic\n- Updated `todoApi.ts` with batch reorder endpoint support\n- `backend/routes/todos.py` — New `PUT /api/todos/reorder` batch endpoint\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can grab a todo by its drag handle and drag it to a new position — the list reorders smoothly during the drag\n- A visual placeholder shows where the item will be dropped\n- The dragged item has a subtle shadow/elevation effect while being dragged\n- After dropping, the new order persists across page refreshes (saved to backend)\n- User can select a todo and press Alt+Up or Alt+Down to move it up/down in the list — same visual animation plays\n- Adding a new todo animates it sliding into the list\n- Deleting a todo animates it sliding out\n- Reordering 20+ items feels smooth with no visible jank or layout shift\n- The reorder API accepts a batch of `{id, position}` pairs and updates all positions atomically\n- Screen readers announce reorder changes (e.g., \"Task moved to position 3 of 7\")\n\n### Technical Notes\n- `@dnd-kit` is the recommended library — it's accessible, performant, and framework-agnostic\n- Use `@dnd-kit/sortable` preset for list reordering\n- Optimistic updates: update local state immediately, then sync to server; revert on failure\n- Batch reorder endpoint should accept an array of `{id, position}` and update all in a single SQLite transaction\n- Use `framer-motion` or CSS transitions for add/remove animations (`AnimatePresence` for exit animations)\n- Keyboard reorder: listen for Alt+Arrow keys when a todo is focused, update position in store and API\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 4: Offline Storage & Service Worker\n\n### Scope\n- Set up IndexedDB as the local data store using the `idb` library\n- Implement a service worker for offline detection and asset caching\n- Build the sync queue system for pending mutations\n- Add online/offline status indicator in the UI\n- Ensure the app loads and functions fully without a network connection\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/db/indexedDb.ts` — IndexedDB wrapper with typed CRUD operations\n- `frontend/src/db/syncQueue.ts` — Queue for pending mutations (create, update, delete, reorder)\n- `frontend/src/sw.ts` — Service worker for caching app shell and API responses\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useOnlineStatus.ts` — Hook for detecting online/offline state\n- `frontend/src/components/OfflineIndicator.tsx` — Visual banner/badge showing connection status\n- Updated `todoStore.ts` — reads from IndexedDB, writes to both IndexedDB and sync queue\n- `vite.config.ts` — Updated with `vite-plugin-pwa` for service worker build\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can add, edit, delete, and reorder todos while completely offline — all changes are persisted in IndexedDB\n- Refreshing the page while offline loads all todos from IndexedDB (not a blank screen or error)\n- A subtle offline indicator (banner or badge) appears when the network is unavailable\n- The indicator disappears when the connection is restored\n- While offline, mutations are queued in a sync queue (visible in IndexedDB via DevTools)\n- The service worker caches the app shell (HTML, JS, CSS) so the app loads instantly on repeat visits, even offline\n- After going offline, adding 5 todos, and coming back online, all 5 todos appear on the server within 10 seconds\n- Opening the app for the first time with no network shows an appropriate \"first visit requires network\" message (since there's no cached data yet)\n- IndexedDB stores todos with the same schema as the API response (id, title, completed, position, created_at, updated_at)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `idb` library (wrapper around IndexedDB) for cleaner async/await API\n- Sync queue entries: `{ id, type: 'create'|'update'|'delete'|'reorder', payload, timestamp, retryCount }`\n- Service worker strategy: Cache-First for static assets, Network-First for API calls (falling back to IndexedDB)\n- Use `vite-plugin-pwa` with `workbox` for service worker generation and precaching\n- Online detection: combine `navigator.onLine` with periodic pings to `/health` endpoint for reliability\n- Store a `syncVersion` counter in IndexedDB to track local changes vs server state\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 5: Background Sync & Conflict Resolution\n\n### Scope\n- Implement background sync that replays the mutation queue when connectivity returns\n- Handle sync conflicts using last-write-wins with timestamp comparison\n- Add retry logic with exponential backoff for failed syncs\n- Show sync status in the UI (syncing, synced, conflict, error)\n- Handle edge cases: duplicate creates, out-of-order operations, partial failures\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncEngine.ts` — Background sync orchestrator\n- `frontend/src/sync/conflictResolver.ts` — Conflict detection and resolution logic\n- `frontend/src/components/SyncStatus.tsx` — Sync status indicator (icon + tooltip)\n- `backend/routes/sync.py` — New `POST /api/sync` endpoint for batch sync operations\n- `backend/schemas.py` — Updated with sync-specific request/response models\n- `backend/tests/test_sync.py` — Tests for conflict scenarios\n- Updated service worker with Background Sync API registration\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- After going offline, making 10 changes, and reconnecting, all changes sync to the server in correct order within 15 seconds\n- The sync status indicator shows: a checkmark when synced, a spinner when syncing, a warning icon when there are unsynced changes\n- Hovering over the sync indicator shows \"3 changes pending\" (with actual count)\n- If the server has a newer version of a todo (edited on another device/tab), the server version wins and the local copy is updated\n- If sync fails due to a network error, it retries with exponential backoff (1s, 2s, 4s, 8s, max 30s)\n- After 5 consecutive sync failures, a \"Sync failed — tap to retry\" message appears\n- Deleting a todo offline that was already deleted on the server does not cause an error (idempotent)\n- Creating a todo offline generates a temporary UUID; after sync, it's replaced with the server-assigned ID transparently\n- The `POST /api/sync` endpoint accepts an array of operations and returns results for each, including conflicts\n- `pytest backend/tests/test_sync.py` passes with all conflict scenarios covered\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use the Background Sync API (`registration.sync.register`) in the service worker for reliable sync\n- Fallback: if Background Sync API is not available, use `setInterval` polling when online\n- Conflict resolution: compare `updated_at` timestamps — server wins if server timestamp > local timestamp\n- Temporary IDs: generate UUIDs client-side for offline creates; server returns a mapping of `{temp_id: real_id}` after sync\n- Batch sync endpoint should process operations in order and return per-operation results: `{status: 'ok'|'conflict'|'error', data: ...}`\n- Use database transactions for atomicity — either all operations in a batch succeed or none do\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 6: Filtering, Search & Bulk Actions\n\n### Scope\n- Add filter tabs: All, Active, Completed\n- Implement instant search/filter with highlighted matches\n- Add bulk actions: mark all complete, delete completed, select multiple\n- Add todo count indicators and progress visualization\n- Implement keyboard shortcuts for power users\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/FilterBar.tsx` — Filter tabs with count badges\n- `frontend/src/components/SearchInput.tsx` — Search input with debounced filtering\n- `frontend/src/components/BulkActions.tsx` — Bulk action toolbar\n- `frontend/src/components/ProgressBar.tsx` — Visual progress indicator\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useKeyboardShortcuts.ts` — Global keyboard shortcut handler\n- `frontend/src/components/KeyboardShortcutHelp.tsx` — Help modal showing available shortcuts\n- Updated store with filter/search state and derived selectors\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Three filter tabs (All, Active, Completed) are visible above the todo list, each showing a count badge (e.g., \"Active (5)\")\n- Clicking a filter tab instantly filters the list — no loading state needed since it's client-side\n- A search input filters todos as the user types (debounced by 150ms) — matching text is highlighted in the results\n- Searching for \"milk\" with todos \"Buy milk\" and \"Drink milk\" highlights \"milk\" in both items\n- A \"Clear completed\" button appears when completed todos exist — clicking it deletes all completed todos with a confirmation\n- A \"Mark all complete\" checkbox in the header toggles all todos' completed state\n- A progress bar or ring shows \"5 of 12 completed\" with visual fill\n- Keyboard shortcuts work: `n` to focus new todo input, `/` to focus search, `?` to show shortcut help, `Escape` to clear search/filters\n- The shortcut help modal lists all available shortcuts and is dismissible with Escape or clicking outside\n- All filters and search work identically in offline mode (filtering local IndexedDB data)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Filters should be URL-driven (`?filter=active&q=milk`) so they survive page refreshes\n- Use `useMemo` for filtered/searched todo lists to avoid recomputation\n- Debounce search input with `useDeferredValue` or a custom debounce hook\n- Highlight matches using a `<mark>` tag or a `Highlight` component that splits text around the match\n- Bulk delete should show a confirmation dialog, then optimistically remove items and sync\n- Store keyboard shortcut definitions in a config object for easy customization\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 7: Polish, Animations & Accessibility\n\n### Scope\n- Refine all animations and transitions for a premium feel\n- Implement full keyboard navigation and screen reader support\n- Add dark mode with system preference detection and manual toggle\n- Add micro-interactions: checkbox animation, delete sweep, success feedback\n- Performance optimization: virtual scrolling for large lists, optimized re-renders\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/ThemeToggle.tsx` — Dark/light mode toggle\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` — Theme management with system preference detection\n- `frontend/src/styles/themes.css` — CSS custom properties for light and dark themes\n- `frontend/src/components/VirtualTodoList.tsx` — Virtualized list for performance with large datasets\n- Updated components with ARIA attributes, roles, and live regions\n- Animation refinements across all interactive elements\n- `frontend/src/components/FocusTrap.tsx` — Focus trap for modals and dialogs\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Toggling a todo's checkbox plays a satisfying animation (e.g., checkmark draws in, strikethrough sweeps across)\n- Deleting a todo shows a brief slide-out or fade animation before removal\n- Adding a todo shows a slide-in animation from the top of the list\n- Dark mode activates automatically based on system preference (`prefers-color-scheme`)\n- A toggle in the header switches between dark and light mode — the preference persists across sessions\n- In dark mode, all text is readable (WCAG AA contrast ratio 4.5:1 minimum), and the design feels intentional (not just inverted colors)\n- All interactive elements are reachable via Tab key in logical order\n- Screen readers announce: todo count changes, filter switches, sync status updates, and drag-and-drop results (via `aria-live` regions)\n- With 500 todos in the list, scrolling feels smooth (60fps) thanks to virtualization\n- The app scores 90+ on Lighthouse accessibility audit\n- Focus is trapped inside modals (shortcut help, confirmations) and returns to the trigger element on close\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use CSS custom properties (`--color-bg`, `--color-text`, etc.) for theming — toggle a `data-theme` attribute on `<html>`\n- Store theme preference in `localStorage`, falling back to `prefers-color-scheme` media query\n- Use `@tanstack/react-virtual` for list virtualization — only render visible items plus a small overscan buffer\n- Animations: prefer CSS transitions/animations over JS for performance; use `framer-motion` only for complex orchestrated sequences\n- ARIA: `role=\"list\"` on container, `role=\"listitem\"` on items, `aria-live=\"polite\"` for count announcements, `aria-grabbed`/`aria-dropeffect` for DnD\n- Test with VoiceOver (macOS) and the axe DevTools browser extension\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 8: Testing, Error Boundaries & Production Readiness\n\n### Scope\n- Achieve 80%+ test coverage across frontend and backend\n- Add React error boundaries for graceful failure handling\n- Implement comprehensive E2E tests for critical user flows\n- Add structured logging, error tracking, and performance monitoring\n- Production build optimization and deployment configuration\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/ErrorBoundary.tsx` — Catches rendering errors with recovery UI\n- `frontend/src/__tests__/` — Unit tests for all components, hooks, and store (Vitest + Testing Library)\n- `frontend/e2e/` — Playwright E2E tests for critical flows\n- `backend/tests/` — Expanded pytest suite with edge cases and error scenarios\n- `docker-compose.yml` — Development and production Docker setup\n- `Dockerfile.frontend` and `Dockerfile.backend` — Optimized multi-stage builds\n- `.github/workflows/ci.yml` — CI pipeline: lint, type-check, test, build\n- `frontend/src/utils/logger.ts` — Structured logging utility\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `npm run test` in frontend passes with 80%+ line coverage (reported by Vitest)\n- `pytest --cov` in backend passes with 80%+ line coverage\n- E2E tests cover: add todo, edit todo, delete todo, reorder todo, filter todos, offline mode, sync after reconnect\n- All E2E tests pass in headless Chromium via Playwright\n- If a component throws during render, the error boundary catches it and shows \"Something went wrong\" with a \"Try again\" button (not a white screen)\n- `docker-compose up` starts both frontend and backend, accessible at `localhost:3000` (frontend) and `localhost:8000` (backend)\n- The production frontend build is under 200KB gzipped (excluding images)\n- The CI pipeline runs in under 5 minutes and fails on: lint errors, type errors, test failures, or coverage below threshold\n- Backend logs include structured JSON with request ID, timestamp, method, path, status, and duration for every request\n- API errors return consistent error response format: `{\"error\": {\"code\": \"NOT_FOUND\", \"message\": \"Todo not found\"}}`\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use Vitest (not Jest) for frontend tests — it integrates natively with Vite\n- Testing Library: test user behavior, not implementation details (`getByRole`, `userEvent`, not `querySelector`)\n- E2E: use Playwright's network interception to simulate offline mode in tests\n- Error boundaries: wrap the main app, individual route sections, and the todo list separately for granular recovery\n- Docker: multi-stage builds — `node:20-alpine` for frontend build, `python:3.12-slim` for backend\n- CI: parallelize frontend and backend test jobs; cache `node_modules` and `.venv`\n- Structured logging: use Python's `structlog` library for JSON-formatted backend logs\n",
