            "content": "# Todo App — Build Plan\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThis is not just another todo app — it's a fast, resilient, offline-first task manager that feels native on the web. The core promise: your tasks are always accessible, always responsive, and never lost. Whether you're on a plane, in a tunnel, or just have flaky wifi, every interaction — adding, editing, reordering, completing — works instantly and syncs seamlessly when connectivity returns.\n\nThe app pairs a React + TypeScript frontend (built with Vite for instant dev feedback) with a FastAPI + SQLite backend. SQLite is the perfect fit: zero-config, embedded, and battle-tested for single-user productivity tools. The frontend maintains its own local persistence layer (IndexedDB) so the UI never blocks on the network. A lightweight sync protocol reconciles local and remote state using timestamps and a simple conflict resolution strategy (last-write-wins with user notification).\n\nBeyond the basics, the app aims for polish: smooth drag-and-drop reordering with optimistic UI updates, keyboard-first navigation for power users, subtle animations that make state transitions feel intentional, and a clean, opinionated design system that makes the interface a pleasure to use. The scoring weights emphasize design quality and originality — this plan reflects that by investing heavily in interaction design, visual craft, and thoughtful details that elevate the experience beyond a CRUD form.\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                   Frontend                       │\n│  React 18 + TypeScript + Vite                    │\n│                                                  │\n│  ┌───────────┐  ┌────────────┐  ┌─────────────┐ │\n│  │ Components │  │ State Mgmt │  │ Local Store  │ │\n│  │ (UI Layer) │  │ (Zustand)  │  │ (IndexedDB)  │ │\n│  └─────┬─────┘  └─────┬──────┘  └──────┬──────┘ │\n│        │               │                │        │\n│        └───────┬───────┘                │        │\n│                │                        │        │\n│         ┌──────┴──────┐         ┌───────┴──────┐ │\n│         │  API Client │         │  Sync Engine │ │\n│         │  (fetch)    │◄───────►│  (offline)   │ │\n│         └──────┬──────┘         └──────────────┘ │\n└────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┘\n                 │ HTTP/JSON\n┌────────────────┼────────────────────────────────┐\n│                │       Backend                   │\n│         ┌──────┴──────┐                          │\n│         │   FastAPI    │                          │\n│         │   Router     │                          │\n│         └──────┬──────┘                          │\n│         ┌──────┴──────┐                          │\n│         │  Service     │                          │\n│         │  Layer       │                          │\n│         └──────┬──────┘                          │\n│         ┌──────┴──────┐                          │\n│         │  Repository  │                          │\n│         │  (SQLite)    │                          │\n│         └─────────────┘                          │\n│  Python 3.12+ / FastAPI / aiosqlite              │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n**Key architectural decisions:**\n\n- **State management**: Zustand — lightweight, TypeScript-native, no boilerplate. Stores are immutable (produce new state, never mutate).\n- **Local persistence**: IndexedDB via `idb` library — async, structured, handles large datasets. Every mutation writes locally first, then syncs.\n- **Sync protocol**: Operation log with timestamps. Each todo mutation is recorded as an operation. The sync engine replays unsynced operations to the server and pulls remote changes. Conflicts resolved by `updated_at` timestamp (last-write-wins).\n- **Backend layering**: Router → Service → Repository. The repository pattern abstracts SQLite access behind an async interface. Services contain business logic. Routers handle HTTP concerns only.\n- **Reordering**: Fractional indexing (using a `position` float column) — allows inserting between any two items without rewriting all positions. Periodic normalization keeps precision clean.\n- **Testing**: pytest for backend, Vitest for frontend, Playwright for E2E.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 1: Project Skeleton & Backend Foundation\n\n### Scope\n- Initialize monorepo structure with frontend and backend directories\n- Set up Vite + React + TypeScript frontend with dev server\n- Set up FastAPI backend with SQLite database\n- Implement the data model and repository layer\n- Create the full CRUD REST API for todos\n- Add request/response validation with Pydantic models\n- Write comprehensive backend tests\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/` — Vite project with React, TypeScript, working dev server\n- `frontend/package.json` — dependencies configured\n- `frontend/tsconfig.json` — strict TypeScript config\n- `frontend/vite.config.ts` — dev server with API proxy to backend\n- `backend/` — FastAPI project structure\n- `backend/pyproject.toml` or `backend/requirements.txt` — Python dependencies\n- `backend/app/main.py` — FastAPI app entry point with CORS\n- `backend/app/models.py` — Pydantic request/response models\n- `backend/app/database.py` — SQLite connection and schema initialization\n- `backend/app/repository.py` — Todo repository (CRUD + reorder)\n- `backend/app/service.py` — Business logic layer\n- `backend/app/router.py` — REST API routes\n- `backend/tests/` — pytest test suite\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Running `npm run dev` in `frontend/` starts Vite dev server on a local port and displays a placeholder page\n- Running `uvicorn app.main:app` in `backend/` starts the API server\n- `GET /api/todos` returns 200 with an empty JSON array initially\n- `POST /api/todos` with `{\"title\": \"Buy milk\"}` returns 201 with the created todo including `id`, `title`, `completed`, `position`, `created_at`, `updated_at` fields\n- `GET /api/todos` returns the created todo in the array\n- `PATCH /api/todos/{id}` with `{\"title\": \"Buy oat milk\"}` returns 200 with updated todo; `updated_at` has changed\n- `PATCH /api/todos/{id}` with `{\"completed\": true}` returns 200 with `completed: true`\n- `DELETE /api/todos/{id}` returns 204; subsequent GET returns empty array\n- `POST /api/todos` with empty title returns 422 with validation error\n- `GET /api/todos/nonexistent-id` returns 404 with error message\n- `PATCH /api/todos/{id}` with `{\"position\": 2.5}` updates the position field\n- All backend tests pass with `pytest` and cover the repository, service, and router layers\n- SQLite database file is created automatically on first run\n- API responses follow envelope format: consistent JSON structure\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `aiosqlite` for async SQLite access in FastAPI\n- Use UUIDs (v4) for todo IDs — generated server-side\n- Schema: `id TEXT PRIMARY KEY, title TEXT NOT NULL, completed BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE, position REAL NOT NULL, created_at TEXT NOT NULL, updated_at TEXT NOT NULL`\n- Timestamps in ISO 8601 format (UTC)\n- Position for new todos: query MAX(position) + 1.0, default to 1.0 if empty\n- CORS must allow the frontend dev server origin\n- Use `httpx.AsyncClient` for testing FastAPI (no real server needed)\n- Repository functions return new objects, never mutate inputs\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 2: Core UI — Todo List & CRUD Interactions\n\n### Scope\n- Build the main todo list component connected to the backend API\n- Implement add, edit, complete, and delete interactions\n- Set up Zustand store for todo state management\n- Create a typed API client layer\n- Establish the design system (colors, typography, spacing)\n- Add loading and empty states\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/stores/todoStore.ts` — Zustand store with async actions\n- `frontend/src/api/todoApi.ts` — Typed API client (fetch-based)\n- `frontend/src/api/types.ts` — Shared TypeScript interfaces matching backend models\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoList.tsx` — Main list component\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — Individual todo row with edit/complete/delete\n- `frontend/src/components/AddTodo.tsx` — Input for adding new todos\n- `frontend/src/components/EmptyState.tsx` — Shown when no todos exist\n- `frontend/src/styles/` — Design tokens and global styles (CSS modules or Tailwind config)\n- `frontend/src/App.tsx` — Composed layout\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Opening the app in a browser shows the todo list (empty state if no todos)\n- Typing in the add input and pressing Enter creates a new todo that appears in the list without page reload\n- Clicking a checkbox on a todo toggles its completed state; completed todos show a strikethrough or visual distinction\n- Double-clicking a todo title enters inline edit mode; pressing Enter saves the edit; pressing Escape cancels\n- Each todo has a visible delete button/icon; clicking it removes the todo from the list\n- After refreshing the page, all todos persist (loaded from backend)\n- The empty state shows a friendly message and visual (not just blank space)\n- Loading state shows a skeleton or spinner while fetching\n- Error state shows a user-friendly message if the API is unreachable\n- The UI has a cohesive design: consistent colors, readable typography, comfortable spacing\n- Input validation: cannot add a todo with empty/whitespace-only title; input shows inline feedback\n- All text is properly truncated with ellipsis if it overflows\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Zustand store should be fully typed with TypeScript interfaces\n- Store actions must be immutable: produce new arrays/objects, never mutate state\n- API client should handle errors uniformly and return typed results\n- Use optimistic updates where possible (update UI immediately, rollback on error)\n- Consider `React.memo` on TodoItem for performance with large lists\n- CSS approach: CSS modules or Tailwind CSS — pick one and commit to it\n- Minimum touch target: 44px for interactive elements (accessibility)\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 3: Drag-and-Drop Reordering\n\n### Scope\n- Implement drag-and-drop reordering of todos using a modern DnD library\n- Add backend endpoint for batch reorder\n- Smooth animations during drag operations\n- Persist new order to backend\n- Keyboard-accessible reordering alternative\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/SortableTodoList.tsx` — DnD-enabled list wrapper\n- `frontend/src/components/DragHandle.tsx` — Visual drag affordance\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useReorder.ts` — Reorder logic and position calculation\n- `backend/app/router.py` — Updated with `PUT /api/todos/reorder` endpoint\n- Backend tests for reorder endpoint\n- Frontend tests for reorder interactions\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Each todo item displays a visible drag handle (grip icon) on the left side\n- Clicking and dragging the handle moves the todo to a new position in the list with a smooth animation\n- The dragged item has a visual \"picked up\" state (slight elevation/shadow, reduced opacity on source)\n- A visual drop indicator shows where the item will land\n- After dropping, the new order persists — refreshing the page shows the same order\n- Dragging the first item to the last position works correctly\n- Dragging the last item to the first position works correctly\n- Reordering with only 2 items in the list works correctly\n- The `position` values in the database reflect the new order after reorder\n- Keyboard users can reorder: selecting an item and pressing Alt+Up/Alt+Down moves it\n- Screen reader announces position changes (e.g., \"Task moved to position 3 of 5\")\n- Reorder API call uses fractional indexing — does not rewrite all positions on every move\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `@dnd-kit/core` and `@dnd-kit/sortable` — modern, accessible, performant\n- Fractional indexing: when moving item between positions A and B, new position = (A + B) / 2\n- If precision gets too low (positions too close), trigger a normalization pass on the backend\n- Optimistic reorder: update UI immediately, sync to backend in background\n- DnD sensors: pointer (mouse/touch) and keyboard\n- Add `will-change: transform` on dragging items for GPU-accelerated animation\n- Debounce rapid reorder API calls (e.g., 300ms after last drop)\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 4: Offline Storage & Local Persistence\n\n### Scope\n- Implement IndexedDB local storage for todos\n- Create an operation log for tracking offline mutations\n- Build a local-first data flow: all reads/writes go through local store first\n- Add network status detection\n- Ensure the app is fully functional with no backend running\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/storage/db.ts` — IndexedDB setup using `idb` library\n- `frontend/src/storage/todoStorage.ts` — Local CRUD operations for todos\n- `frontend/src/storage/operationLog.ts` — Operation log for pending sync operations\n- `frontend/src/storage/types.ts` — Storage-specific types\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useNetworkStatus.ts` — Online/offline detection hook\n- `frontend/src/stores/todoStore.ts` — Updated to read/write locally first\n- Frontend tests for local storage operations\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- With the backend running: adding a todo saves it both locally (IndexedDB) and remotely (API)\n- Stopping the backend and refreshing the page: all todos still appear (loaded from IndexedDB)\n- With the backend stopped: adding a new todo works — it appears in the list immediately\n- With the backend stopped: editing a todo works — changes are visible immediately\n- With the backend stopped: completing a todo works\n- With the backend stopped: deleting a todo works\n- With the backend stopped: reordering todos works\n- The operation log correctly records all mutations made while offline (verifiable in browser DevTools → IndexedDB)\n- A visual indicator shows online/offline status (e.g., subtle banner or icon in the header)\n- The offline indicator appears within 3 seconds of losing connectivity\n- No console errors or crashes when performing any operation offline\n- IndexedDB data persists across browser sessions (close and reopen browser)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use the `idb` library (lightweight Promise wrapper for IndexedDB)\n- Database schema: `todos` object store (keyed by `id`) + `operations` object store (auto-incremented)\n- Operation log entries: `{ id, type: 'create'|'update'|'delete'|'reorder', payload, timestamp }`\n- The store should try API first (optimistic), fall back to local-only on network error\n- `navigator.onLine` for basic detection, plus `fetch` ping for reliable detection\n- Service Worker is NOT needed yet — just IndexedDB persistence\n- All storage functions must be async and handle IndexedDB errors gracefully\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 5: Sync Engine — Online/Offline Reconciliation\n\n### Scope\n- Build the sync engine that reconciles local and remote state\n- Replay pending operations when coming back online\n- Handle conflicts (same todo edited offline and on server)\n- Add sync status indicators per todo\n- Backend endpoint for bulk sync\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncEngine.ts` — Core sync logic\n- `frontend/src/sync/conflictResolver.ts` — Conflict detection and resolution\n- `frontend/src/sync/types.ts` — Sync-specific types\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useSyncStatus.ts` — Hook for sync state\n- `frontend/src/components/SyncIndicator.tsx` — Global sync status UI\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoSyncBadge.tsx` — Per-item sync status\n- `backend/app/router.py` — `POST /api/todos/sync` bulk sync endpoint\n- `backend/app/sync_service.py` — Server-side sync logic\n- Backend and frontend tests for sync scenarios\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Going offline, making changes, then coming back online: all changes sync to the server within 5 seconds\n- After sync, refreshing the page and checking the API directly confirms data is consistent\n- Adding 3 todos offline, then reconnecting: all 3 appear on the server\n- Editing a todo offline, then reconnecting: the edit appears on the server\n- Deleting a todo offline, then reconnecting: the todo is deleted on the server\n- A global sync indicator shows: \"Synced\" (green), \"Syncing...\" (animated), \"X changes pending\" (yellow), or \"Sync error\" (red)\n- Each unsynced todo shows a small badge indicating it hasn't been synced yet\n- After successful sync, badges disappear\n- If the sync endpoint returns an error, the pending operations are retained and retried on next sync attempt\n- Operations are replayed in chronological order (FIFO)\n- Duplicate sync prevention: the same operation is not sent twice even if the user triggers sync manually\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Sync trigger: on `online` event + periodic poll (every 30 seconds when online)\n- Conflict resolution strategy: last-write-wins based on `updated_at` timestamps\n- The `/api/todos/sync` endpoint accepts an array of operations and returns the current server state\n- Server processes operations idempotently (re-sending the same create doesn't duplicate)\n- Use exponential backoff for retry on sync failure (1s, 2s, 4s, max 30s)\n- Clear operation log entries only after server confirms successful processing\n- Consider a `sync_version` or `etag` field for future optimistic concurrency\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 6: Visual Polish & Animations\n\n### Scope\n- Add thoughtful animations and transitions throughout the app\n- Implement a refined visual design with attention to detail\n- Add micro-interactions for delight (hover states, focus rings, completion celebration)\n- Dark mode support\n- Responsive layout for mobile and desktop\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/styles/theme.ts` — Theme tokens with light/dark variants\n- `frontend/src/styles/animations.ts` or CSS — Shared animation definitions\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` — Theme toggle with system preference detection\n- `frontend/src/components/ThemeToggle.tsx` — Light/dark mode switch\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — Updated with animations\n- `frontend/src/components/CompletionEffect.tsx` — Celebration micro-interaction\n- Updated global styles for responsive breakpoints\n- All components updated for dark mode compatibility\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Adding a todo: the new item slides in from the top with a subtle fade animation\n- Completing a todo: a satisfying visual effect plays (e.g., confetti burst, checkmark animation, or strikethrough sweep)\n- Deleting a todo: the item collapses smoothly out of the list; remaining items slide up\n- Hovering over a todo highlights it with a subtle background shift\n- Focus is clearly visible on all interactive elements (keyboard navigation shows focus ring)\n- The app has a dark mode toggle in the header area\n- Dark mode colors have sufficient contrast (WCAG AA: 4.5:1 for text)\n- The app defaults to the user's system color scheme preference\n- On mobile (< 640px): the layout adapts — full-width items, larger touch targets, no hover-dependent UI\n- On tablet (640px–1024px): comfortable reading width, centered content\n- On desktop (> 1024px): max content width with elegant centering\n- Animations respect `prefers-reduced-motion` — users who disable animations see instant state changes\n- The overall visual impression is clean, modern, and intentional — not a default/unstyled app\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use CSS transitions for simple state changes, CSS keyframe animations or Framer Motion for complex sequences\n- Theme implementation: CSS custom properties (variables) toggled by a data attribute on `<html>`\n- Persist theme preference to `localStorage`\n- Use `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` for initial load, then allow manual override\n- `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce` → set all `transition-duration` and `animation-duration` to 0\n- Completion effect: keep it brief (< 600ms) and non-blocking\n- Test on Chrome, Firefox, and Safari for animation consistency\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 7: Keyboard Navigation & Accessibility\n\n### Scope\n- Full keyboard navigation throughout the app\n- ARIA roles and labels for screen reader support\n- Focus management for dynamic content (add, delete, edit operations)\n- Keyboard shortcuts for power users\n- Accessibility audit and fixes\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useKeyboardShortcuts.ts` — Global keyboard shortcut handler\n- `frontend/src/components/KeyboardShortcutsHelp.tsx` — Shortcut reference overlay (triggered by `?`)\n- Updated ARIA attributes on all interactive components\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useFocusManagement.ts` — Focus trap and restore logic\n- Frontend tests for keyboard interactions\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Pressing `/` focuses the add-todo input from anywhere in the app\n- Pressing `?` opens a keyboard shortcuts help overlay\n- In the todo list: `j`/`k` or Arrow Down/Up navigates between items (visible focus indicator)\n- On a focused todo: `Enter` enters edit mode, `Space` toggles completion, `Backspace` or `Delete` deletes (with confirmation)\n- On a focused todo: `Alt+Up`/`Alt+Down` reorders (from Sprint 3)\n- `Escape` closes any open overlay, exits edit mode, or blurs the current input\n- Tab order is logical: add input → first todo → second todo → ... → theme toggle\n- When a todo is deleted, focus moves to the next item (or previous if last item was deleted)\n- When a todo is added, focus moves to the newly created item\n- Screen reader announces: list count (\"5 items\"), item completion (\"Task completed\"), reorder position\n- All images/icons have appropriate `alt` text or `aria-label`\n- No `aria-hidden` content is focusable\n- Color is not the only indicator of state (completed todos have both color AND strikethrough/icon)\n- The app scores 0 errors on axe-core automated accessibility check\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `role=\"listbox\"` or `role=\"list\"` with `role=\"option\"`/`role=\"listitem\"` for the todo list\n- `aria-live=\"polite\"` region for announcing dynamic changes (add/delete/reorder/sync)\n- Focus management: use `useRef` and `element.focus()` after state updates (in `useEffect`)\n- Keyboard shortcuts should not conflict with browser defaults\n- Shortcuts should be disabled when an input/textarea is focused (except `Escape`)\n- Use `tabindex=\"-1\"` for programmatically focusable but not tab-order elements\n- Consider `@axe-core/react` for development-time accessibility warnings\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 8: Service Worker & Full PWA\n\n### Scope\n- Register a Service Worker for true offline capability\n- Cache app shell and static assets\n- Add Web App Manifest for installability\n- Implement app install prompt\n- Background sync for pending operations\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/public/manifest.json` — Web App Manifest\n- `frontend/public/icons/` — App icons in multiple sizes (192x192, 512x512 minimum)\n- `frontend/src/sw.ts` or `frontend/public/sw.js` — Service Worker\n- `frontend/src/pwa/registerSW.ts` — SW registration and update logic\n- `frontend/src/components/InstallPrompt.tsx` — \"Add to Home Screen\" prompt\n- `frontend/src/components/UpdateNotification.tsx` — \"New version available\" notification\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- The app loads and is fully interactive even with airplane mode enabled (after first visit)\n- Chrome DevTools → Application → Manifest shows valid manifest with app name and icons\n- Chrome DevTools → Application → Service Workers shows an active service worker\n- Lighthouse PWA audit passes all requirements (installable, works offline, has manifest)\n- On mobile Chrome: \"Add to Home Screen\" option appears in browser menu\n- A custom install prompt appears on first visit (dismissable, doesn't reappear after dismissal)\n- Navigating to the app URL offline shows the cached app (not Chrome's dinosaur page)\n- Deploying a new version shows an \"Update available\" notification; clicking it refreshes to the new version\n- Static assets (JS, CSS, icons) are served from cache on subsequent visits (faster load)\n- API requests tha