            "content": "# Todo App — Build Plan\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThe Todo App is a polished, offline-first task management application that feels snappy and reliable whether the user is on a fast connection, spotty Wi-Fi, or completely offline. Unlike minimal todo demos, this app treats task management as a first-class workflow: users can add, edit, delete, and — critically — reorder items with smooth drag-and-drop, and every change syncs seamlessly once connectivity returns.\n\nThe backend is a lightweight FastAPI service backed by SQLite, providing a clean REST API that doubles as the sync target for the offline-capable frontend. The frontend is a React + TypeScript application bundled with Vite, designed with attention to interaction details — optimistic UI updates, graceful conflict resolution, and subtle animations that make reordering feel physical and satisfying.\n\nThe product aspires to be a reference-quality example of an offline-first CRUD app: small in scope but deep in craft. Every sprint ships something visible, from the initial API skeleton to the final service-worker-powered offline mode with background sync. The scoring rubric prioritizes design quality and originality, so the app will push beyond the expected with thoughtful micro-interactions, keyboard accessibility, and a distinctive visual identity.\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n### System Overview\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                   Browser                    │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌───────────┐ │\n│  │  React    │  │ IndexedDB│  │  Service   │ │\n│  │  UI       │◄─┤  Store   │  │  Worker    │ │\n│  │ (Vite)   │  │ (offline)│  │ (SW cache) │ │\n│  └────┬─────┘  └────┬─────┘  └─────┬─────┘ │\n│       │              │              │        │\n│       └──────┬───────┘              │        │\n│              │  Sync Engine         │        │\n│              └──────────────────────┘        │\n└──────────────────┬───────────────────────────┘\n                   │ REST API (JSON)\n┌──────────────────┴───────────────────────────┐\n│              FastAPI Backend                   │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌────────────┐ │\n│  │ Routers  │  │ Services │  │ Repository │ │\n│  │ (CRUD +  │──│ (business│──│ (SQLite    │ │\n│  │  reorder)│  │  logic)  │  │  via aio-  │ │\n│  └──────────┘  └──────────┘  │  sqlite)   │ │\n│                               └────────────┘ │\n└───────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Key Architectural Decisions\n\n- **Repository pattern** for data access — SQLite behind an async interface, easily testable with in-memory databases.\n- **Immutable state updates** on the frontend — React state never mutated in place; all updates produce new objects.\n- **Optimistic UI** — the frontend applies changes immediately and reconciles with the server asynchronously.\n- **IndexedDB** as the offline store — mirrors the server schema locally, enabling full CRUD while offline.\n- **Service Worker** for asset caching and background sync — the app shell loads instantly even without a network.\n- **Fractional indexing** for reorder — positions stored as fractional values to avoid renumbering entire lists on every drag.\n\n### API Envelope\n\nAll API responses follow a consistent format:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"success\": true,\n  \"data\": { ... },\n  \"error\": null,\n  \"meta\": { \"total\": 42, \"page\": 1, \"limit\": 20 }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 1: Project Skeleton & Backend CRUD\n\n### Scope\n- Initialize the monorepo with frontend (Vite + React + TypeScript) and backend (FastAPI + SQLite) directories.\n- Set up the build system, linting, formatting, and dev scripts.\n- Implement the core backend CRUD API for todos (create, read, update, delete).\n- Add basic integration tests for all endpoints.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/` — FastAPI app with `main.py`, `routers/todos.py`, `services/todo_service.py`, `repositories/todo_repository.py`, `models/todo.py`, `database.py`.\n- `frontend/` — Vite + React + TypeScript scaffold with `App.tsx` placeholder.\n- `backend/tests/` — pytest integration tests for CRUD endpoints.\n- `README.md` with setup instructions.\n- SQLite database schema with `todos` table (`id`, `title`, `description`, `completed`, `position`, `created_at`, `updated_at`).\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `POST /api/todos` with `{\"title\": \"Buy milk\"}` returns 201 with the created todo including `id`, `title`, `completed: false`, `position`, and timestamps.\n- `GET /api/todos` returns 200 with a JSON body containing `success: true` and `data` as an array of todos ordered by `position`.\n- `PATCH /api/todos/{id}` with `{\"title\": \"Updated\"}` returns 200 with the updated todo.\n- `DELETE /api/todos/{id}` returns 200 and the todo is no longer returned by GET.\n- All tests pass with `pytest` and achieve ≥80% coverage of backend code.\n- `npm run dev` starts the Vite dev server without errors.\n- `uvicorn` starts the FastAPI server without errors.\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `aiosqlite` for async SQLite access.\n- Use Pydantic v2 models for request/response validation.\n- Position field uses float values (fractional indexing) — default to incrementing integers on creation.\n- Set up `pyproject.toml` with dev dependencies (pytest, pytest-asyncio, httpx for test client).\n- Frontend uses `vite create` with the React + TypeScript template.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 2: Frontend Todo List & API Integration\n\n### Scope\n- Build the core todo list UI in React.\n- Wire up the frontend to the FastAPI backend.\n- Implement add, toggle complete, edit inline, and delete operations.\n- Set up a clean component architecture.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoList.tsx`, `TodoItem.tsx`, `AddTodo.tsx`, `EditableTodoTitle.tsx`.\n- `frontend/src/api/todoApi.ts` — typed API client using fetch.\n- `frontend/src/types/todo.ts` — TypeScript interfaces matching backend models.\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useTodos.ts` — custom hook managing todo state and API calls.\n- Vite proxy config routing `/api` to the FastAPI backend.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can type a todo title and press Enter or click \"Add\" to create a new todo; it appears in the list immediately.\n- User can click a checkbox to toggle a todo's completed state; the UI updates immediately and the change persists on reload.\n- User can double-click a todo title to edit it inline; pressing Enter saves, Escape cancels.\n- User can click a delete button to remove a todo; it disappears from the list immediately.\n- Empty title submission is rejected with a visible error message.\n- The todo list renders correctly with 0, 1, and 50+ items.\n- All API errors display a user-friendly toast/notification (not a raw error).\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use optimistic updates: apply changes to local state before the API call resolves, roll back on failure.\n- Keep components small and focused — each under 100 lines.\n- Use CSS modules or a utility-first approach (Tailwind or similar) — avoid global CSS.\n- Frontend tests not required this sprint but component structure should be testable.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 3: Drag-and-Drop Reorder\n\n### Scope\n- Implement drag-and-drop reordering of todos in the frontend.\n- Add a backend endpoint for reordering.\n- Use fractional indexing for efficient position updates.\n- Add smooth animations during drag operations.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/DraggableTodoList.tsx` — wraps the todo list with drag-and-drop capability.\n- `backend/routers/todos.py` — new `PATCH /api/todos/{id}/reorder` endpoint.\n- `frontend/src/utils/fractionalIndex.ts` — utility for computing positions between two adjacent items.\n- Animation CSS/transitions for drag feedback.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can drag a todo item and drop it between two other items; the new order persists on page reload.\n- During drag, the held item has a visual lift effect (shadow, scale, or opacity change) and a drop indicator shows the target position.\n- Reordering a single item sends exactly one API call (not N calls to update all positions).\n- Reordering works correctly at list boundaries (drag to first position, drag to last position).\n- The reorder animation completes in under 300ms with no visual jank.\n- Keyboard reorder: user can select an item and use Alt+Up / Alt+Down to move it; the change persists.\n- Backend returns 400 if the target position is invalid.\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `@dnd-kit/core` and `@dnd-kit/sortable` for drag-and-drop (or equivalent lightweight library).\n- Fractional indexing: when inserting between positions 1.0 and 2.0, assign 1.5. When inserting between 1.0 and 1.5, assign 1.25. Periodically rebalance if precision gets too deep.\n- The reorder endpoint accepts `{ \"after_id\": \"uuid-or-null\", \"before_id\": \"uuid-or-null\" }` and computes the new position server-side.\n- Add a rebalance mechanism that normalizes positions to integers when gaps get too small (< 0.001).\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 4: Visual Design & Micro-Interactions\n\n### Scope\n- Establish a distinctive visual identity — not a generic todo app look.\n- Add polish: transitions, hover states, focus rings, loading skeletons.\n- Implement responsive layout for mobile and desktop.\n- Add a dark mode toggle.\n\n### Deliverables\n- Design system tokens: `frontend/src/styles/tokens.css` (colors, spacing, typography, shadows).\n- `frontend/src/components/ThemeToggle.tsx` — dark/light mode switch with system preference detection.\n- Loading skeleton component for initial data fetch.\n- Responsive layout that works from 320px to 1440px.\n- Subtle animations: item enter/exit, checkbox ripple, delete slide-out.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- The app has a cohesive color palette with at least primary, secondary, surface, and error colors — not default browser styling.\n- Dark mode toggles instantly with a smooth transition; preference persists in localStorage.\n- On first load with slow network (throttled to 3G), a skeleton loader is visible instead of a blank screen.\n- New todos animate in (fade + slide); deleted todos animate out (slide + fade).\n- The checkbox has a custom design with a satisfying completion animation (e.g., checkmark draws in, strikethrough animates across the title).\n- The app is usable at 320px width (mobile) without horizontal scrolling.\n- All interactive elements have visible focus indicators for keyboard navigation.\n- The favicon and page title reflect the app's identity (not default Vite favicon).\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use CSS custom properties for theming — switch themes by toggling a class on `<html>`.\n- Prefer CSS animations/transitions over JavaScript animation libraries for performance.\n- Use `prefers-color-scheme` media query for initial theme, then respect user override.\n- Consider a subtle background pattern or gradient to add visual depth.\n- Test on Chrome, Firefox, and Safari (or at least Chrome + one other).\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 5: Frontend Testing & Accessibility\n\n### Scope\n- Add comprehensive frontend tests (unit + integration).\n- Ensure full keyboard accessibility.\n- Add ARIA labels and screen reader support.\n- Implement error boundary and graceful degradation.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/__tests__/` — Vitest + React Testing Library tests for all components and hooks.\n- `frontend/src/components/ErrorBoundary.tsx` — catches rendering errors gracefully.\n- ARIA attributes on all interactive elements.\n- Keyboard navigation for all features including drag-and-drop reorder.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Frontend test coverage ≥ 80% as reported by Vitest.\n- A screen reader (VoiceOver or NVDA) can navigate the entire todo list: add, edit, complete, delete, and reorder items with announcements.\n- Tab order follows a logical flow: add input → todo items (checkbox → title → actions) → theme toggle.\n- All color combinations meet WCAG AA contrast ratios (4.5:1 for text, 3:1 for large text).\n- The ErrorBoundary catches a simulated rendering error and displays a friendly \"Something went wrong\" message with a retry button.\n- All existing functionality still works after accessibility additions (no regressions).\n- Tests cover: adding a todo, editing a todo, deleting a todo, toggling completion, reordering, empty state, error state.\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `@testing-library/react` with `@testing-library/user-event` for realistic interaction testing.\n- Use `vitest` as the test runner (integrates with Vite).\n- For accessibility testing, add `jest-axe` (or `vitest-axe`) to run automated a11y checks in tests.\n- Use `role`, `aria-label`, `aria-live` regions for dynamic updates (e.g., \"Todo added\", \"Todo deleted\").\n- Error boundary should log errors to console in dev, and could POST to a logging endpoint in production.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 6: Offline Storage with IndexedDB\n\n### Scope\n- Implement a local IndexedDB store that mirrors the server's todo data.\n- Add a sync status indicator (synced / pending / offline).\n- All CRUD operations work offline using the local store.\n- Changes queue for sync when connectivity returns.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/db/todoDb.ts` — IndexedDB wrapper using `idb` library (or Dexie.js).\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncQueue.ts` — queues mutations as operations to replay against the server.\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncEngine.ts` — orchestrates local-first reads and background sync.\n- `frontend/src/components/SyncStatus.tsx` — visual indicator of sync state.\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useTodosOffline.ts` — replaces `useTodos.ts`, reads from IndexedDB first.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- With network disabled (DevTools offline mode), user can add, edit, delete, and reorder todos; all changes persist in IndexedDB.\n- A sync status badge shows \"Offline\" (yellow) when disconnected and \"Synced\" (green) when all changes are pushed.\n- After reconnecting, pending changes sync to the server within 5 seconds without user action.\n- After sync, the data on the server matches the local state (verified by refreshing the page).\n- If the app is closed while offline and reopened (still offline), all local changes are retained.\n- The sync queue handles at least 20 queued operations correctly (ordered, no duplicates, no data loss).\n- Concurrent edits to the same todo (offline edit + server edit) use last-write-wins resolution and don't crash.\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use the `idb` library for a promise-based IndexedDB wrapper — it's small and well-maintained.\n- The sync queue stores operations as `{ type: 'create'|'update'|'delete'|'reorder', payload: {...}, timestamp: number }`.\n- On reconnect, replay operations in order. For conflicts, use last-write-wins based on `updated_at` timestamps.\n- Listen for `online`/`offline` events on `window` to update sync status.\n- IndexedDB schema should match the server schema to simplify sync logic.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 7: Service Worker & PWA Shell\n\n### Scope\n- Add a service worker for asset caching (app shell loads without network).\n- Configure the app as a Progressive Web App (installable).\n- Implement background sync via the Service Worker API.\n- Add an app manifest with icons and theme colors.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/public/manifest.json` — PWA manifest with app name, icons, theme color, display mode.\n- `frontend/src/sw.ts` — service worker handling cache-first for assets, network-first for API.\n- App icons at multiple resolutions (at least 192x192 and 512x512).\n- `frontend/vite.config.ts` updated with `vite-plugin-pwa` configuration.\n- Offline fallback page for uncached routes.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- After first visit, the app loads fully (shell + cached data) with no network connection.\n- Chrome's Lighthouse PWA audit passes with a score ≥ 90.\n- The app can be installed to the home screen on Android Chrome and desktop Chrome (\"Add to Home Screen\" prompt appears).\n- Static assets (JS, CSS, images) are served from cache on subsequent visits (verified in DevTools Network tab: \"ServiceWorker\" source).\n- API responses are cached with a network-first strategy: fresh data when online, cached data when offline.\n- The service worker updates gracefully: when a new version is deployed, the user sees an \"Update available\" prompt; clicking it activates the new worker.\n- Background sync: if a mutation fails due to network, the service worker retries it when connectivity returns.\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `vite-plugin-pwa` with `workbox` for service worker generation — avoids hand-writing cache strategies.\n- Cache strategy: **CacheFirst** for static assets (hashed filenames), **NetworkFirst** for API calls.\n- Use Workbox's `BackgroundSyncPlugin` for queuing failed API mutations.\n- Generate icons from a single SVG source using a build script.\n- Test by toggling offline in DevTools and verifying the app still functions.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 8: Backend Hardening & Advanced Features\n\n### Scope\n- Add input validation, rate limiting, and error handling to the backend.\n- Implement pagination and filtering on the todo list endpoint.\n- Add bulk operations (bulk delete completed, bulk toggle).\n- Add backend unit tests to reach ≥ 80% coverage.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/middleware/rate_limit.py` — simple in-memory rate limiter.\n- `backend/middleware/error_handler.py` — global exception handler returning consistent error envelope.\n- Updated `GET /api/todos` with query params: `?page=1&limit=20&completed=true&search=milk`.\n- `POST /api/todos/bulk-delete` and `POST /api/todos/bulk-toggle` endpoints.\n- `backend/tests/` — comprehensive test suite with ≥ 80% coverage.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `GET /api/todos?page=2&limit=5` returns the second page of 5 todos with `meta.total`, `meta.page`, `meta.limit` in the response.\n- `GET /api/todos?search=milk` returns only todos whose title contains \"milk\" (case-insensitive).\n- `GET /api/todos?completed=true` returns only completed todos.\n- `POST /api/todos` with an empty title returns 422 with `{\"success\": false, \"error\": \"Title is required\"}`.\n- `POST /api/todos` with a title exceeding 500 characters returns 422 with a descriptive error.\n- Rate limiter returns 429 after 100 requests per minute from the same client.\n- `POST /api/todos/bulk-delete` with `{\"ids\": [\"id1\", \"id2\"]}` deletes both and returns 200.\n- `POST /api/todos/bulk-toggle` with `{\"ids\": [\"id1\", \"id2\"], \"completed\": true}` marks both complete.\n- Backend test coverage ≥ 80% (pytest-cov report).\n- Invalid JSON body returns 400 (not 500).\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Rate limiting can use a simple dict with timestamps — no need for Redis at this scale.\n- Use FastAPI's built-in validation via Pydantic; add custom validators for title length and content.\n- Search uses SQL `LIKE` with proper escaping of special characters (`%`, `_`).\n- Bulk operations should be atomic — all succeed or all fail (use a transaction).\n- Error handler should catch `Exception`, log the traceback, and return a sanitized error message (no stack traces in production).\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 9: Frontend-Backend Integration Polish\n\n### Scope\n- Wire up pagination, search/filter, and bulk operations in the frontend.\n- Add a \"Clear completed\" button and a completion progress bar.\n- Add undo for delete operations (soft delete with timed undo).\n- Final integration testing — all features work end-to-end online and offline.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoFilters.tsx` — filter bar (All / Active / Completed) + search input.\n- `frontend/src/components/ProgressBar.tsx` — shows X of Y todos completed.\n- `frontend/src/components/UndoToast.tsx` — toast with \"Undo\" button that appears after delete, auto-dismisses after 5 seconds.\n- Updated sync engine to handle pagination and filters in offline mode.\n- Integration test suite covering full user workflows.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can switch between \"All\", \"Active\", and \"Completed\" filters; the list updates instantly.\n- User can type in the search box; results filter as-you-type with a 300ms debounce.\n- A progress bar shows \"3 of 7 completed\" with a filled segment proportional to completion.\n- After deleting a todo, an \"Undo\" toast appears for 5 seconds; clicking \"Undo\" restores the todo.\n- If \"Undo\" is not clicked within 5 seconds, the deletion is finalized.\n- \"Clear completed\" button removes all completed todos with a single click; an undo toast appears.\n- All filters and search work while offline (filtering local IndexedDB data).\n- Pagination loads more items seamlessly (infinite scroll or \"Load more\" button).\n- The app handles 500+ todos without noticeable lag (scrolling remains smooth).\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Debounce search input to avoid excessive API calls / IndexedDB queries.\n- Undo uses soft delete: mark as `deleted_at` timestamp, only finalize after timeout or on next sync.\n- Progress bar can use a simple CSS width transition for smooth animation.\n- Virtual scrolling (e.g., `react-virtual` / `@tanstack/virtual`) may be needed for 500+ items.\n- Offline filters should query IndexedDB directly — use Dexie's `.where()` or IDB cursors.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 10: Final Polish, Performance & Deployment\n\n### Scope\n- Performance optimization: bundle size, lazy loading, render performance.\n- Add onboarding empty state with a friendly illustration or message.\n- Final visual polish pass — consistency check across all states.\n- Production build configuration and deployment readiness.\n- End-to-end tests for critical flows.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/EmptyState.tsx` — engaging empty state with illustration and CTA.\n- Vite production config with code splitting, tree shaking, and compression.\n- `Dockerfile` and `docker-compose.yml` for single-command deployment.\n- `frontend/e2e/` — Playwright E2E tests for critical user flows.\n- Performance budget: JS bundle < 150KB gzipped, LCP < 1.5s, TTI < 2s.\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Empty state: when there are no todos, a friendly message and illustration are shown (not a blank list).\n- Lighthouse Performance score ≥ 90 on production build.\n- Lighthouse Accessibility score ≥ 95.\n- Total JS bundle size < 150KB gzipped (verified by Vite build output).\n- `docker compose up` starts both backend and frontend, app is accessible at `http://localhost:3000`.\n- E2E tests cover: add todo → edit → reorder → complete → filter → delete → undo → offline mode.\n- All E2E tests pass in headless Chromium.\n- The app works correctly after a hard refresh (Ctrl+Shift+R) — no stale service worker issues.\n- No console errors or warnings in production build.\n- The app loads in under 2 seconds on a simulated 4G connection.\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `vite build --report` to analyze bundle size; identify and eliminate large dependencies.\n- Lazy-load non-critical components (ThemeToggle, filters) with `React.lazy` + `Suspense`.\n- Use `terser` or `esbuild` minification (Vite default).\n- Docker setup: multi-stage build for frontend (build → nginx), simple Python image for backend.\n- E2E tests should use Playwright's `page.route()` to mock API responses for deterministic tests, plus one true integration test against the real backend.\n- Final checklist: favicons, meta tags, Open Graph tags, robots.txt, 404 page.\n",
