            "content": "# Todo App — Build Plan\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThis is not just another todo app — it's a thoughtfully crafted productivity tool that works seamlessly whether you're online or completely disconnected. The app combines a React frontend with a FastAPI backend and SQLite storage to deliver a fast, reliable task management experience. The core interaction model centers on fluid manipulation of tasks: adding, editing, removing, and — critically — reordering items with drag-and-drop that feels physical and responsive.\n\nThe offline-first architecture is the defining technical challenge and the key differentiator. Rather than treating offline as an error state, the app embraces it as a first-class mode of operation. Users can create, edit, reorder, and delete tasks while disconnected, and changes sync gracefully when connectivity returns. Conflict resolution is handled transparently, with the UI communicating sync status without interrupting the user's flow.\n\nThe design should feel minimal but intentional — clean typography, smooth animations on reorder, subtle visual feedback on every interaction. The app should feel like a native tool, not a web page. Performance is paramount: instant response to every tap and keystroke, with network operations happening invisibly in the background.\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n### Frontend (React + Vite + TypeScript)\n- **Vite** for fast dev server and optimized production builds\n- **React 18+** with functional components and hooks\n- **State management**: Local state with a sync layer — tasks live in IndexedDB for offline persistence, with a sync queue that replays mutations against the backend when online\n- **Drag-and-drop**: A reorder system (e.g., `@dnd-kit/sortable`) that updates fractional position indices for O(1) reorder operations\n- **Service Worker**: Caches the app shell for full offline capability; intercepts API calls and routes to IndexedDB when offline\n- **CSS**: CSS Modules or Tailwind CSS for scoped, utility-first styling with animations\n\n### Backend (FastAPI + Python 3.12+ + SQLite)\n- **FastAPI** with async endpoints and Pydantic v2 models for request/response validation\n- **SQLite** via `aiosqlite` for async database access — single-file database, zero config\n- **Repository pattern**: Data access abstracted behind a repository interface\n- **Migrations**: Simple SQL migration system (or Alembic) for schema evolution\n- **API envelope**: Consistent `{ success, data, error }` response format across all endpoints\n- **CORS**: Configured for local development and production origins\n\n### Offline Sync Architecture\n- Each task mutation (create, update, delete, reorder) is logged to a local **operation queue** in IndexedDB\n- When online, the queue is replayed against the backend in order\n- Server returns a **sync timestamp**; client uses this for incremental sync\n- Conflicts resolved with **last-write-wins** using server timestamps, with client notification on conflicts\n- **Optimistic UI**: All changes appear instantly; sync happens in the background\n\n### Data Model\n```\nTodo {\n  id: UUID\n  title: string (1-500 chars)\n  description: string (optional, max 2000 chars)\n  completed: boolean\n  position: float  // fractional indexing for O(1) reorder\n  created_at: datetime\n  updated_at: datetime\n  deleted_at: datetime | null  // soft delete for sync\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 1: Project Skeleton & Core Backend\n\n### Scope\n- Initialize the full project structure: frontend (Vite + React + TypeScript) and backend (FastAPI + Python)\n- Set up the SQLite database with schema and migration system\n- Implement core CRUD API endpoints for todos\n- Establish the API response envelope pattern\n- Basic health check and CORS configuration\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/main.py` — FastAPI application entry point\n- `backend/models.py` — Pydantic models for Todo\n- `backend/database.py` — SQLite connection and initialization\n- `backend/repository.py` — Todo repository with CRUD operations\n- `backend/routes/todos.py` — REST endpoints\n- `backend/migrations/001_initial.sql` — Initial schema\n- `frontend/` — Vite + React + TypeScript scaffold with a placeholder page\n- `frontend/src/api/client.ts` — API client module\n- `requirements.txt` and `package.json` with all dependencies\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `GET /health` returns `200` with `{ \"status\": \"ok\" }`\n- `POST /api/todos` with `{ \"title\": \"Test\" }` returns `201` with the created todo including `id`, `title`, `completed: false`, `position`, `created_at`, `updated_at`\n- `GET /api/todos` returns `200` with a list of all todos sorted by position\n- `GET /api/todos/{id}` returns `200` with the specific todo, or `404` if not found\n- `PUT /api/todos/{id}` with `{ \"title\": \"Updated\" }` returns `200` with the updated todo\n- `DELETE /api/todos/{id}` returns `204` and the todo is soft-deleted (not returned in GET list)\n- `POST /api/todos` with empty title returns `422` with a validation error message\n- `POST /api/todos` with title exceeding 500 characters returns `422`\n- Frontend runs on `localhost:5173` and displays a placeholder \"Todo App\" heading\n- Backend runs on `localhost:8000` with CORS allowing the frontend origin\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `aiosqlite` for async SQLite access\n- Pydantic v2 with `model_validator` for input validation\n- Fractional indexing: new todos get `position = max(position) + 1.0`; this will be used for reordering later\n- Soft delete via `deleted_at` timestamp — filter out in queries by default\n- Use UUID4 for todo IDs (generated server-side)\n- Set up `pyproject.toml` or `requirements.txt` for Python deps\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 2: Frontend Todo List & CRUD UI\n\n### Scope\n- Build the main todo list UI with add, edit, complete, and delete functionality\n- Connect frontend to the backend API\n- Implement inline editing of todo titles\n- Visual feedback for completed items\n- Empty state and loading states