          "input": {
            "content": "# Todo App — Build Plan\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThis isn't just another todo list — it's a fast, offline-first personal task manager that feels native on the web. The app lets you capture, organize, and reorder tasks with zero friction, whether you're online or disconnected on a plane. Every interaction — adding, editing, dragging, completing — should feel instantaneous because it is: all writes hit a local store first, then sync to the backend when connectivity returns.\n\nThe backend is a lightweight FastAPI service backed by SQLite, designed for single-user simplicity with room to grow. The API is clean and RESTful, with optimistic concurrency handling so offline edits merge gracefully. The frontend is a Vite-powered React SPA with TypeScript, featuring smooth drag-and-drop reordering, inline editing, keyboard shortcuts, and subtle animations that make task management feel satisfying rather than tedious.\n\nThe offline story is the differentiator. Using IndexedDB as a local mirror and a queue-based sync engine, the app works identically whether connected or not. A visible sync indicator keeps the user informed without being intrusive. Conflict resolution follows a last-write-wins strategy with timestamp-based ordering, keeping the implementation pragmatic while handling the common cases well.\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                    Frontend                      │\n│  React + TypeScript + Vite                       │\n│                                                  │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌───────────┐  ┌──────────────┐  │\n│  │ UI Layer │──│ State Mgmt│──│ Sync Engine  │  │\n│  │ Components│  │ (Zustand) │  │ (Queue+IDB) │  │\n│  └──────────┘  └───────────┘  └──────┬───────┘  │\n│                                       │          │\n│  Service Worker (offline shell)       │          │\n└───────────────────────────────────────┼──────────┘\n                                        │ HTTP/JSON\n┌───────────────────────────────────────┼──────────┐\n│                    Backend            │          │\n│  FastAPI + Python 3.12+              │          │\n│                                       │          │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌───────────┐  ┌──────┴───────┐  │\n│  │ Routes   │──│ Services  │──│ Repository   │  │\n│  │ (API)    │  │ (Logic)   │  │ (SQLite)     │  │\n│  └──────────┘  └───────────┘  └──────────────┘  │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n**Key architectural decisions:**\n\n- **Zustand** for state management — lightweight, immutable-friendly, no boilerplate\n- **IndexedDB** (via idb) as the offline data store — structured, async, well-supported\n- **Operation queue** for offline sync — queued mutations replay on reconnect\n- **Repository pattern** on the backend — SQLite access behind an interface\n- **Fractional indexing** for reordering — avoids renumbering all items on every drag\n- **Service Worker** for offline shell caching — app loads even without network\n- **CORS middleware** on FastAPI — frontend served separately during dev\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 1: Project Skeleton & Core Backend\n\n### Scope\n- Initialize the monorepo structure with frontend and backend directories\n- Set up Vite + React + TypeScript with strict config\n- Set up FastAPI with SQLite database and migrations\n- Implement the core todo CRUD API endpoints\n- Establish the repository pattern for data access\n- Add health check endpoint and basic error handling\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/` — FastAPI app with `main.py`, `models.py`, `repository.py`, `routes/todos.py`\n- `backend/requirements.txt` or `pyproject.toml` with dependencies\n- `backend/database.py` — SQLite connection and schema initialization\n- `frontend/` — Vite + React + TypeScript scaffolding with `vite.config.ts`, `tsconfig.json`\n- `frontend/package.json` with dependencies\n- `frontend/src/App.tsx` — minimal shell rendering \"Todo App\"\n- Database schema: `todos` table with `id`, `title`, `completed`, `position`, `created_at`, `updated_at`\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Running `pip install -r requirements.txt && uvicorn main:app` starts the backend on port 8000\n- `GET /health` returns `{\"status\": \"ok\"}`\n- `POST /api/todos` with `{\"title\": \"Buy milk\"}` returns 201 with JSON containing `id`, `title`, `completed: false`, `position`, `created_at`\n- `GET /api/todos` returns 200 with a JSON array of all todos sorted by `position`\n- `GET /api/todos/{id}` returns 200 with the specific todo or 404 if not found\n- `PUT /api/todos/{id}` with `{\"title\": \"Buy oat milk\", \"completed\": true}` returns 200 with updated todo\n- `DELETE /api/todos/{id}` returns 204 and the todo is no longer returned by GET\n- Running `npm install && npm run dev` in `frontend/` starts the Vite dev server\n- Frontend renders a heading \"Todo App\" in the browser\n- All API responses follow the envelope format: `{\"data\": ..., \"error\": null}`\n- Invalid input (empty title, title > 500 chars) returns 422 with descriptive error message\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `aiosqlite` for async SQLite access in FastAPI\n- Create the database and tables on app startup using a lifespan event\n- Use Pydantic models for request/response validation\n- Position field should be a float to support fractional indexing later\n- CORS middleware should allow `http://localhost:5173` (Vite default)\n- Use `uuid4` for todo IDs to simplify offline ID generation later\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 2: Frontend Todo List UI\n\n### Scope\n- Build the main todo list view with add, complete, and delete functionality\n- Implement an API client service for communicating with the backend\n- Set up Zustand store for todo state management\n- Style the app with a clean, modern design system\n- Add loading and error states\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/stores/todoStore.ts` — Zustand store with todos state and actions\n- `frontend/src/api/todoApi.ts` — typed API client with fetch wrapper\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoList.tsx` — main list component\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — individual todo row with checkbox and delete\n- `frontend/src/components/AddTodo.tsx` — input form for adding new todos\n- `frontend/src/components/EmptyState.tsx` — friendly empty state when no todos exist\n- `frontend/src/styles/` — CSS modules or a global stylesheet with design tokens\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can type a todo title and press Enter or click \"Add\" to create it; the todo appears in the list immediately\n- User can click a checkbox to toggle a todo's completed state; completed todos show a strikethrough style\n- User can click a delete button on a todo to remove it; the todo disappears from the list\n- Empty input submission is prevented — the add button is disabled and pressing Enter does nothing\n- When the list is empty, a friendly empty state message is displayed (not a blank screen)\n- Loading spinner or skeleton appears while initial todos are being fetched\n- If the API is unreachable, an error message is displayed to the user (not a blank screen or console error only)\n- The design uses a consistent color palette, readable typography (16px+ body), and comfortable spacing\n- The layout is centered, max-width ~600px, and looks good on both desktop and mobile viewports\n- All interactions (add, toggle, delete) persist to the backend — refreshing the page shows the same state\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use Zustand with immutable update patterns (spread or `immer` middleware)\n- API client should be a thin wrapper around `fetch` with typed responses\n- Use CSS custom properties for the design token system (colors, spacing, radii)\n- TodoItem should be its own component to prepare for drag-and-drop in Sprint 3\n- Optimistic updates in the store: update UI immediately, then send API request; revert on failure\n- Use `React.memo` on TodoItem to avoid unnecessary re-renders in the list\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 3: Inline Editing & Drag-and-Drop Reordering\n\n### Scope\n- Add inline editing — double-click or tap a todo to edit its title in place\n- Implement drag-and-drop reordering with smooth animations\n- Add a reorder API endpoint on the backend\n- Implement fractional indexing for position management\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — updated with inline edit mode (double-click to edit, Enter to save, Escape to cancel)\n- `frontend/src/components/DragHandle.tsx` — visual grip indicator for dragging\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useDragAndDrop.ts` — custom hook or library integration for DnD\n- `backend/routes/todos.py` — new `PATCH /api/todos/{id}/reorder` endpoint\n- `backend/services/position.py` — fractional index calculation logic\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Double-clicking a todo title switches it to an editable text input pre-filled with the current title\n- Pressing Enter in the edit input saves the new title and exits edit mode\n- Pressing Escape in the edit input discards changes and exits edit mode\n- Clicking outside the edit input saves the change (blur-to-save)\n- Empty title is rejected during edit — the input shows a validation hint and the original title is preserved\n- User can drag a todo by its drag handle and drop it at a new position in the list\n- During drag, the dragged item is visually lifted (shadow/scale) and a drop indicator shows the target position\n- After drop, the new order persists — refreshing the page shows the reordered list\n- `PATCH /api/todos/{id}/reorder` with `{\"after_id\": \"<uuid>\"}` or `{\"after_id\": null}` (move to top) returns 200 with updated position\n- Reordering 100 todos does not require updating more than 1 row in the database (fractional indexing)\n- Keyboard users can access edit mode via Enter key when a todo is focused\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Consider `@dnd-kit/core` for drag-and-drop — lightweight, accessible, React-friendly\n- Fractional indexing: new position = average of neighbors' positions. If precision degrades (positions too close), rebalance in a batch\n- The reorder endpoint should accept `after_id` (the item this todo should be placed after) and compute the new position server-side\n- Inline edit should use a controlled input with local state — don't update the store until save\n- Add `will-change: transform` to dragged items for smooth GPU-accelerated animation\n- Debounce edit saves if implementing auto-save on keystroke (but prefer explicit Enter-to-save)\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 4: Keyboard Shortcuts & Micro-interactions\n\n### Scope\n- Add comprehensive keyboard navigation and shortcuts\n- Implement animations for add, complete, delete, and reorder transitions\n- Add a filter bar (All / Active / Completed) with item counts\n- Polish the overall UX with thoughtful micro-interactions\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useKeyboardShortcuts.ts` — global shortcut handler\n- `frontend/src/components/FilterBar.tsx` — All / Active / Completed tabs with counts\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — updated with animation classes\n- `frontend/src/components/ShortcutHint.tsx` — subtle shortcut hints in the UI\n- Updated CSS with transition and animation definitions\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Pressing `N` (when not in an input) focuses the add-todo input\n- Pressing `Escape` from the add-todo input blurs it\n- Arrow keys navigate between todo items (visible focus ring on the active item)\n- Pressing `Space` on a focused todo toggles its completion\n- Pressing `Delete` or `Backspace` on a focused todo deletes it (with confirmation if not completed)\n- Pressing `E` or `Enter` on a focused todo enters edit mode\n- Newly added todos animate in with a slide-down + fade-in effect\n- Deleted todos animate out with a fade-out + collapse effect\n- Completing a todo shows a brief satisfying animation (e.g., checkmark bounce or strikethrough sweep)\n- Filter bar shows three options: \"All (N)\", \"Active (N)\", \"Completed (N)\" where N is the count\n- Clicking a filter shows only matching todos; the URL does not change (client-side filter only)\n- A small `?` button or footer shows available keyboard shortcuts in a modal/tooltip\n- All animations respect `prefers-reduced-motion` — they are disabled when the user prefers reduced motion\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `useEffect` with `keydown` listener for global shortcuts; prevent conflicts with input fields\n- CSS transitions for most animations (height, opacity, transform); use `@keyframes` for the completion celebration\n- Filter state lives in the Zustand store alongside the todos\n- Item counts should derive from the store (not separate API calls)\n- Use `aria-live` regions so screen readers announce filter changes\n- Consider `framer-motion` for complex animations, but CSS-only is fine if simpler\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 5: Offline Storage with IndexedDB\n\n### Scope\n- Set up IndexedDB as a local mirror of all todo data\n- Implement a sync-aware data layer that reads from IndexedDB and writes to both local and remote\n- Add an operation queue for mutations made while offline\n- Build a connectivity detector and sync status indicator\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/db/indexedDb.ts` — IndexedDB wrapper using `idb` library (typed CRUD operations)\n- `frontend/src/sync/operationQueue.ts` — queue that stores pending mutations with timestamps\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncEngine.ts` — orchestrates reading from IDB, writing to IDB + API, and replaying queued operations\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useOnlineStatus.ts` — reactive online/offline detector\n- `frontend/src/components/SyncIndicator.tsx` — visual sync status (synced, syncing, offline with N pending changes)\n- Updated `todoStore.ts` — now reads/writes through the sync engine instead of directly to the API\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- On first load with network, todos are fetched from the API and stored in IndexedDB\n- On subsequent loads, todos are displayed instantly from IndexedDB while a background refresh occurs\n- When offline (network disconnected or airplane mode), adding a todo succeeds — it appears in the list immediately\n- When offline, editing and deleting todos also work — changes are reflected in the UI instantly\n- When offline, reordering todos works — the new order is preserved locally\n- A sync indicator in the header shows the current state: a green dot for \"synced\", a spinning icon for \"syncing\", or an orange dot with \"3 pending\" for offline changes\n- When connectivity returns, pending operations replay automatically in order — no user action required\n- After sync completes, the indicator returns to \"synced\" state\n- If the app is closed while offline and reopened (still offline), the todos and pending operations are preserved\n- IndexedDB contains a `todos` object store and an `operationQueue` object store\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use the `idb` npm package for a Promise-based IndexedDB API with TypeScript support\n- Operation queue entries: `{ id, type: 'create'|'update'|'delete'|'reorder', payload, timestamp }`\n- Sync engine should process the queue sequentially to maintain order consistency\n- Use `navigator.onLine` plus `online`/`offline` events for connectivity detection; supplement with a periodic ping to `/health`\n- When replaying creates, the server may assign a different position — update IDB with the server response\n- Race condition guard: if user makes a new edit while sync is in progress, don't overwrite the newer local state with the older server response\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 6: Service Worker & Full Offline Shell\n\n### Scope\n- Register a service worker that caches the app shell (HTML, JS, CSS, assets)\n- Implement cache-first strategy for static assets, network-first for API calls\n- Ensure the app loads and is fully functional with zero network access\n- Add install prompt (PWA) and manifest\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/public/manifest.json` — PWA manifest with app name, icons, theme color\n- `frontend/public/icons/` — App icons at 192x192 and 512x512\n- `frontend/src/sw.ts` — service worker with caching strategies\n- `frontend/src/registerSW.ts` — service worker registration with update handling\n- `frontend/src/components/UpdatePrompt.tsx` — \"New version available\" notification when SW updates\n- `frontend/vite.config.ts` — updated with `vite-plugin-pwa` configuration\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- After first visit (online), navigating to the app URL with no network loads the full app UI (not a browser error page)\n- The app shell (HTML, CSS, JS) is served from the service worker cache\n- All static assets (fonts, icons) are cached and served offline\n- API requests that fail due to network are gracefully handled (no unhandled promise rejections)\n- `manifest.json` is valid — Chrome DevTools > Application > Manifest shows no errors\n- On mobile Chrome/Safari, the \"Add to Home Screen\" prompt is available\n- When a new version is deployed and the user revisits, a non-intrusive \"Update available — click to refresh\" prompt appears\n- The service worker does not cache API responses (that's IndexedDB's job from Sprint 5)\n- Lighthouse PWA audit scores 90+ on installability and offline capability\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `vite-plugin-pwa` with `workbox` for service worker generation — avoid hand-rolling cache logic\n- Cache strategy: precache the app shell (index.html, JS bundles, CSS); use `NetworkOnly` for API routes\n- Service worker update flow: `skipWaiting()` on user confirmation, then `clients.claim()` and reload\n- Generate icons from a single SVG source — use a simple checklist/hammer icon for branding\n- Test offline behavior in Chrome DevTools > Network > Offline checkbox\n- The manifest `start_url` should be `/` and `display` should be `standalone`\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 7: Conflict Resolution & Sync Robustness\n\n### Scope\n- Implement last-write-wins conflict resolution with server timestamps\n- Add a batch sync endpoint for efficiency\n- Handle edge cases: duplicate creates, out-of-order operations, server errors during sync\n- Add sync retry with exponential backoff\n- Backend versioning field for optimistic concurrency\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/routes/sync.py` — `POST /api/sync` batch endpoint accepting an array of operations\n- `backend/models.py` — updated with `version` field on todos\n- `frontend/src/sync/conflictResolver.ts` — conflict detection and resolution logic\n- `frontend/src/sync/retryStrategy.ts` — exponential backoff with jitter for failed syncs\n- Updated `syncEngine.ts` — uses batch sync and handles conflict responses\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `POST /api/sync` accepts `{\"operations\": [...]}` and returns `{\"results\": [...], \"server_state\": [...]}`\n- When the same todo is edited on two devices (simulated by direct API call + offline edit), the later timestamp wins\n- If an offline delete conflicts with an online edit, the delete wins (delete is authoritative)\n- If an offline create has an ID that already exists on the server, the server returns the existing item (idempotent)\n- After conflict resolution, the client's IndexedDB matches the server's authoritative state\n- Sync retries with exponential backoff: first retry at ~1s, second at ~2s, third at ~4s, max 30s\n- After 5 consecutive sync failures, the sync indicator shows \"Sync error — tap to retry\"\n- Server returns 409 with conflict details when a `version` mismatch is detected on update\n- The `version` field increments on every successful update\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Last-write-wins uses `updated_at` timestamps; the server is the authority on time\n- Batch sync endpoint processes operations transactionally — all succeed or all fail with details\n- Version field enables optimistic concurrency: client sends version with updates, server rejects stale versions\n- Exponential backoff formula: `min(base * 2^attempt + jitter, maxDelay)` where jitter is random 0-500ms\n- Conflict response format: `{\"id\": \"...\", \"status\": \"conflict\", \"serv