sive project documentation\n- `Makefile` — convenience commands: `make dev`, `make build`, `make test`, `make docker-up`\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `docker-compose up` starts both frontend and backend, and the app is accessible at `http://localhost:3000`\n- Frontend in Docker serves the production build through nginx with proper caching headers\n- Backend in Docker uses a SQLite file mounted as a volume (data persists across container restarts)\n- `make dev` starts both frontend and backend in development mode with hot reload\n- `make test` runs all tests (backend + frontend + E2E) and reports combined coverage\n- `.env.example` documents all environment variables with descriptions and default values\n- README includes: project description, quick start (< 5 commands), architecture diagram (ASCII), API documentation, development guide, and deployment notes\n- The full user flow works end-to-end in Docker: add todos, edit, reorder, complete, delete, go offline (stop backend), continue working, restart backend, see sync complete\n- No console errors or warnings in the browser during normal usage\n- The app loads in under 2 seconds on a simulated 3G connection (Lighthouse)\n- All previous sprint acceptance criteria still pass (regression check)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Backend Dockerfile: `python:3.12-slim` base, install deps, copy code, run with `uvicorn`\n- Frontend Dockerfile: `node:20-alpine` for build, `nginx:alpine` for serving; copy build output to nginx html dir\n- Docker Compose: frontend on port 3000, backend on port 8000; frontend nginx proxies `/api` to backend\n- SQLite volume mount: `./data:/app/data` so the database file survives container recreation\n- Makefile should detect OS and use appropriate commands (GNU Make is cross-platform enough)\n- Final smoke test: run the full E2E suite against the Docker Compose stack\n",
