            "content": "# Todo App — Build Plan\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThis isn't just another todo list — it's a fast, offline-first personal task manager that feels native on the web. The app lets you capture, organize, and reorder tasks with zero friction, whether you're online or disconnected on a plane. Every interaction — adding, editing, dragging, completing — should feel instantaneous because it is: all writes hit a local store first, then sync to the backend when connectivity returns.\n\nThe backend is a lightweight FastAPI service backed by SQLite, designed for single-user simplicity with room to grow. The API is clean and RESTful, with optimistic concurrency handling so offline edits merge gracefully. The frontend is a Vite-powered React SPA with TypeScript, featuring smooth drag-and-drop reordering, inline editing, keyboard shortcuts, and subtle animations that make task management feel satisfying rather than tedious.\n\nThe offline story is the differentiator. Using IndexedDB as a local mirror and a queue-based sync engine, the app works identically whether connected or not. A visible sync indicator keeps the user informed without being intrusive. Conflict resolution follows a last-write-wins strategy with timestamp-based ordering, keeping the implementation pragmatic while handling the common cases well. Drawing inspiration from Things 3 and Linear, the UI uses generous whitespace, subtle depth cues, and satisfying micro-interactions. Accessibility, error recovery, and data integrity are first-class concerns, not afterthoughts.\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                    Frontend                      │\n│  React + TypeScript + Vite                       │\n│                                                  │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌───────────┐  ┌──────────────┐  │\n│  │ UI Layer │──│ State Mgmt│──│ Sync Engine  │  │\n│  │ Components│  │ (Zustand) │  │ (Queue+IDB) │  │\n│  └──────────┘  └───────────┘  └──────┬───────┘  │\n│                                       │          │\n│  Service Worker (offline shell)       │          │\n└───────────────────────────────────────┼──────────┘\n                                        │ HTTP/JSON\n┌───────────────────────────────────────┼──────────┐\n│                    Backend            │          │\n│  FastAPI + Python 3.12+              │          │\n│                                       │          │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌───────────┐  ┌──────┴───────┐  │\n│  │ Routes   │──│ Services  │──│ Repository   │  │\n│  │ (API)    │  │ (Logic)   │  │ (SQLite)     │  │\n│  └──────────┘  └───────────┘  └──────────────┘  │\n└──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n**Key architectural decisions:**\n\n- **Zustand** for state management — lightweight, immutable-friendly, no boilerplate\n- **IndexedDB** (via idb) as the offline data store — structured, async, well-supported\n- **Operation queue** for offline sync — queued mutations replay on reconnect\n- **Repository pattern** on the backend — SQLite access behind an interface\n- **Fractional indexing** for reordering — avoids renumbering all items on every drag\n- **Service Worker** for offline shell caching — app loads even without network\n- **CORS middleware** on FastAPI — frontend served separately during dev\n\n**Offline-sync protocol:**\n1. All mutations write to IndexedDB immediately (optimistic updates)\n2. A sync queue records each mutation with a timestamp and operation type\n3. When online, the sync engine replays the queue against the API\n4. Server responds with canonical state; client reconciles\n5. Conflicts detected via `updated_at` timestamps; last-write-wins with user notification\n\n**Data model:**\n- `id`: UUID (generated client-side for offline creates)\n- `title`: string (1-500 chars, required)\n- `completed`: boolean (default false)\n- `position`: float (midpoint insertion for O(1) reorder)\n- `created_at`: ISO 8601 datetime\n- `updated_at`: ISO 8601 datetime\n- `version`: integer (for optimistic concurrency)\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 1: Project Skeleton & Core Backend\n\n### Scope\n- Initialize the monorepo structure with frontend and backend directories\n- Set up Vite + React + TypeScript with strict config\n- Set up FastAPI with SQLite database and schema initialization\n- Implement the core todo CRUD API endpoints\n- Establish the repository pattern for data access\n- Add health check endpoint and basic error handling\n- Write backend tests with pytest\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/main.py` — FastAPI application entry point with CORS middleware and lifespan\n- `backend/database.py` — async SQLite connection and schema initialization using aiosqlite\n- `backend/models.py` — SQLite table definitions\n- `backend/schemas.py` — Pydantic v2 request/response models\n- `backend/repository.py` — TodoRepository with all DB operations\n- `backend/services.py` — Business logic layer\n- `backend/routes/todos.py` — REST API endpoints\n- `backend/tests/test_todos.py` — pytest test suite for all endpoints\n- `backend/requirements.txt` — Python dependencies\n- `frontend/` — Vite + React + TypeScript scaffold\n- `frontend/package.json`, `frontend/tsconfig.json`, `frontend/vite.config.ts`\n- `frontend/src/App.tsx` — minimal shell rendering \"Todo App\"\n- Database schema: `todos` table with `id`, `title`, `completed`, `position`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `version`\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Running `cd backend && pip install -r requirements.txt && python -m uvicorn main:app` starts the server on port 8000\n- `GET /health` returns 200 with `{\"status\": \"ok\"}`\n- `POST /api/todos` with `{\"title\": \"Buy milk\"}` returns 201 with JSON body containing `id`, `title`, `completed` (false), `position`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `version` (1)\n- `GET /api/todos` returns 200 with a JSON array of all todos sorted by `position` ascending\n- `GET /api/todos/{id}` returns 200 with the specific todo, or 404 with error detail\n- `PUT /api/todos/{id}` with `{\"title\": \"Buy oat milk\", \"completed\": true}` returns 200 with the updated todo\n- `DELETE /api/todos/{id}` returns 204 and the todo is no longer returned by GET\n- `PATCH /api/todos/{id}/reorder` with `{\"after_id\": \"<uuid>\"}` returns 200 with updated position\n- `PATCH /api/todos/{id}/reorder` with `{\"after_id\": null}` moves the todo to the first position\n- `POST /api/todos` with `{\"title\": \"\"}` returns 422 with validation error\n- `POST /api/todos` with title exceeding 500 characters returns 422 with validation error\n- All API responses use envelope format: `{\"data\": ..., \"error\": null}` for success, `{\"data\": null, \"error\": {\"message\": \"...\"}}` for errors\n- Running `cd backend && python -m pytest` passes with 80%+ coverage\n- Running `cd frontend && npm install && npm run dev` starts Vite dev server on port 5173\n- Frontend renders a heading \"Todo App\" at `http://localhost:5173`\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `aiosqlite` for async SQLite — keep it lightweight, no ORM\n- Repository pattern: routes -> services -> repository -> database\n- Use float-based positioning for fractional indexing: when inserting between items at 2.0 and 3.0, new position = 2.5\n- Use `uuid4` for todo IDs to simplify offline ID generation later\n- CORS: allow `http://localhost:5173` in development\n- Use `httpx.AsyncClient` with `TestClient` for API tests, in-memory SQLite (`:memory:`) for test isolation\n- Pydantic v2 models: `TodoCreate`, `TodoUpdate`, `TodoResponse`, `TodoReorder`\n- Create database and tables on app startup using a lifespan event\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 2: Frontend Todo List UI\n\n### Scope\n- Build the main todo list view with add, complete, and delete functionality\n- Implement an API client service for communicating with the backend\n- Set up Zustand store for todo state management\n- Style the app with a clean, modern design system using CSS custom properties\n- Add loading and error states\n- Add empty state component\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/types/todo.ts` — TypeScript types matching backend schemas\n- `frontend/src/api/todoApi.ts` — typed API client with fetch wrapper\n- `frontend/src/stores/todoStore.ts` — Zustand store with immutable update patterns\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoList.tsx` — main list container\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — individual todo row with checkbox and delete\n- `frontend/src/components/AddTodo.tsx` — input form for adding new todos\n- `frontend/src/components/EmptyState.tsx` — friendly empty state when no todos exist\n- `frontend/src/components/ErrorBanner.tsx` — error notification banner\n- `frontend/src/components/LoadingSpinner.tsx` — loading indicator\n- `frontend/src/styles/tokens.css` — design token system with CSS custom properties\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- User can type a todo title and press Enter or click \"Add\" to create it; the todo appears in the list immediately\n- User can click a checkbox to toggle a todo's completed state; completed todos show a strikethrough style with CSS transition\n- User can click a delete button (visible on hover) on a todo to remove it; the todo disappears from the list\n- Empty input submission is prevented — the add button is disabled and pressing Enter does nothing\n- When the list is empty, a friendly empty state message \"No todos yet\" is displayed (not a blank screen)\n- Loading spinner or skeleton appears while initial todos are being fetched from the API\n- If the API is unreachable, an error banner is displayed with a descriptive message (not a blank screen or console error only)\n- The design uses a consistent color palette, readable typography (16px+ body), and comfortable spacing via CSS custom properties\n- The layout is centered, max-width ~600px, and looks good on both desktop and mobile viewports\n- All interactions (add, toggle, delete) persist to the backend — refreshing the page shows the same state\n- Todo titles longer than 500 characters are rejected with client-side validation message\n- All interactive elements have visible hover and focus states\n- Optimistic updates: UI updates immediately, reverts with error message on API failure\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use Zustand with immutable update patterns (spread operators, no mutation)\n- API client should be a thin wrapper around `fetch` with typed responses, base URL from `VITE_API_URL` env var\n- Use CSS custom properties for the design token system (colors, spacing, radii, shadows)\n- TodoItem should be its own component to prepare for drag-and-drop in Sprint 3\n- Use `React.memo` on TodoItem to avoid unnecessary re-renders in the list\n- Keep components focused: TodoItem should be < 100 lines\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 3: Inline Editing & Drag-and-Drop Reordering\n\n### Scope\n- Add inline editing — double-click or tap a todo to edit its title in place\n- Implement drag-and-drop reordering with smooth visual feedback\n- Add a drag handle component\n- Implement keyboard-accessible reordering (Alt+Up / Alt+Down)\n- Persist reorder to backend via the reorder API\n- Add basic animations for list mutations\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — updated with inline edit mode (double-click to edit, Enter to save, Escape to cancel)\n- `frontend/src/components/DragHandle.tsx` — visual grip indicator for dragging\n- `frontend/src/components/SortableTodoList.tsx` — dnd-kit powered sortable list\n- `frontend/src/components/SortableTodoItem.tsx` — sortable wrapper for TodoItem\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useTodoReorder.ts` — hook encapsulating reorder logic\n- Updated `todoStore.ts` with optimistic reorder and rollback\n- Updated `todoApi.ts` with reorder support\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Double-clicking a todo title switches it to an editable text input pre-filled with the current title\n- Pressing Enter in the edit input saves the new title and exits edit mode\n- Pressing Escape in the edit input discards changes and exits edit mode\n- Clicking outside the edit input saves the change (blur-to-save)\n- Empty title is rejected during edit — the input shows a validation hint and the original title is preserved\n- Each todo displays a drag handle (grip dots icon) on the left side\n- Grabbing the drag handle and dragging vertically reorders the list in real time\n- The dragged item has a subtle shadow/elevation effect while being dragged\n- A drop indicator shows where the item will be placed\n- After drop, the new order persists — refreshing the page shows the reordered list\n- Dragging the first item to the last position works correctly\n- Dragging the last item to the first position works correctly\n- User can focus a todo and press Alt+Up or Alt+Down to move it up/down\n- Adding a new todo plays a slide-in animation\n- Deleting a todo plays a fade-out + collapse animation\n- Reordering plays a smooth layout shift animation (no teleporting)\n- Keyboard users can access edit mode via Enter key when a todo is focused\n- Screen readers announce position changes: \"Task moved to position 3 of 7\"\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `@dnd-kit/core` and `@dnd-kit/sortable` with PointerSensor and KeyboardSensor\n- Optimistic updates: reorder local state immediately, sync to server, revert on failure\n- Fractional indexing: new position = average of neighbors' positions\n- Inline edit should use a controlled input with local state — don't update the store until save\n- Add `will-change: transform` to dragged items for smooth GPU-accelerated animation\n- ARIA: use `aria-roledescription=\"sortable\"` and announce position changes via live region\n- Consider `framer-motion` for enter/exit animations, or use CSS transitions if simpler\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 4: Keyboard Shortcuts & Micro-interactions\n\n### Scope\n- Add comprehensive keyboard navigation and shortcuts\n- Implement a filter bar (All / Active / Completed) with item counts\n- Add search with highlighted matches\n- Add bulk actions (mark all complete, clear completed)\n- Add progress visualization\n- Add keyboard shortcut help dialog\n- Polish micro-interactions and transitions\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useKeyboardShortcuts.ts` — global shortcut handler\n- `frontend/src/components/FilterBar.tsx` — All / Active / Completed tabs with counts\n- `frontend/src/components/SearchInput.tsx` — search input with debounced filtering\n- `frontend/src/components/BulkActions.tsx` — bulk action toolbar\n- `frontend/src/components/ProgressIndicator.tsx` — visual progress bar\n- `frontend/src/components/KeyboardShortcutHelp.tsx` — help modal listing shortcuts\n- `frontend/src/components/HighlightedText.tsx` — text with search match highlighting\n- `frontend/src/components/ShortcutHint.tsx` — subtle shortcut hints in the UI\n- Updated store with filter, search state, and derived selectors\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Three filter tabs appear above the list: \"All (N)\", \"Active (N)\", \"Completed (N)\" with live counts\n- Clicking \"Active\" shows only incomplete todos; \"Completed\" shows only completed todos\n- The active filter tab has a distinct visual style (underline or background highlight)\n- A search input filters todos by title as the user types (debounced 200ms)\n- Search is case-insensitive: \"buy\" matches \"Buy Milk\"\n- Matching text is highlighted with a `<mark>` element in search results\n- Search with no results shows \"No todos match your search\"\n- A \"Mark all complete\" checkbox in the header toggles all todos\n- A \"Clear completed\" button appears when completed todos exist — clicking removes all completed\n- Progress text shows \"5 of 12 completed\" with a subtle progress bar\n- Pressing `N` (when not in an input) focuses the add-todo input\n- Pressing `Escape` from the add-todo input blurs it; from search, clears search and resets filters\n- Arrow keys navigate between todo items (visible focus ring on the active item)\n- Pressing `Space` on a focused todo toggles its completion\n- Pressing `Delete` or `Backspace` on a focused todo deletes it\n- Pressing `E` or `Enter` on a focused todo enters edit mode\n- Pressing `/` focuses the search input\n- Pressing `?` opens the shortcut help modal\n- The shortcut help modal is dismissible with Escape or clicking outside\n- A small `?` button or footer shows available keyboard shortcuts\n- Completing a todo shows a brief satisfying animation (checkmark bounce or strikethrough sweep)\n- All animations respect `prefers-reduced-motion` — disabled when user prefers reduced motion\n- All filters and search work entirely client-side (no API calls)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `useMemo` for derived filtered/searched todo lists — counts derive from store, not separate calls\n- Debounce with `useDeferredValue` or custom `useDebounce` hook\n- `<HighlightedText>` splits text around matches and wraps in `<mark>`\n- Keyboard shortcuts: register on `document` with `keydown`, check `event.target` to avoid firing in inputs\n- Bulk operations: call individual API endpoints but batch the state updates\n- Use `aria-live` regions so screen readers announce filter changes\n- CSS transitions for most animations; `@keyframes` for completion celebration\n- Consider `framer-motion` for complex animations if needed\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 5: Offline Storage with IndexedDB\n\n### Scope\n- Set up IndexedDB as a local mirror of all todo data\n- Implement a sync-aware data layer that reads from IndexedDB and writes to both local and remote\n- Add an operation queue for mutations made while offline\n- Build a connectivity detector and sync status indicator\n- Ensure all existing features work identically offline\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/db/indexedDb.ts` — IndexedDB wrapper using `idb` library (typed CRUD operations)\n- `frontend/src/sync/operationQueue.ts` — queue that stores pending mutations with timestamps\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncEngine.ts` — orchestrates reading from IDB, writing to IDB + API, and replaying queued operations\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useOnlineStatus.ts` — reactive online/offline detector\n- `frontend/src/components/SyncIndicator.tsx` — visual sync status (synced, syncing, offline with N pending changes)\n- Updated `todoStore.ts` — now reads/writes through the sync engine instead of directly to the API\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- On first load with network, todos are fetched from the API and stored in IndexedDB\n- On subsequent loads, todos are displayed instantly from IndexedDB while a background refresh occurs\n- When offline (network disconnected), adding a todo succeeds — it appears in the list immediately\n- When offline, editing and deleting todos also work — changes are reflected in the UI instantly\n- When offline, reordering todos works — the new order is preserved locally\n- Filtering, searching, and bulk actions all work offline (they operate on local data)\n- A sync indicator in the header shows the current state: green dot for \"synced\", spinning icon for \"syncing\", orange dot with \"3 pending\" for offline changes\n- When connectivity returns, pending operations replay automatically in order — no user action required\n- After sync completes, the indicator returns to \"synced\" state\n- If the app is closed while offline and reopened (still offline), the todos and pending operations are preserved\n- IndexedDB contains a `todos` object store and an `operationQueue` object store (verifiable in DevTools)\n- Refreshing the page while offline loads all todos from IndexedDB (not a blank screen)\n- Opening the app for the first time with no cached data and no network shows a clear \"Connect to get started\" message\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use the `idb` npm package for a Promise-based IndexedDB API with TypeScript support\n- Operation queue entries: `{ id, type: 'create'|'update'|'delete'|'reorder', payload, timestamp }`\n- Sync engine should process the queue sequentially to maintain order consistency\n- Use `navigator.onLine` plus `online`/`offline` events for connectivity detection; supplement with periodic ping to `/health`\n- When replaying creates, the server may assign different data — update IDB with the server response\n- Race condition guard: if user makes a new edit while sync is in progress, don't overwrite newer local state with older server response\n- Generate UUID v4 client-side for todos created offline\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 6: Service Worker & Full Offline Shell\n\n### Scope\n- Register a service worker that caches the app shell (HTML, JS, CSS, assets)\n- Implement cache-first strategy for static assets\n- Ensure the app loads and is fully functional with zero network access\n- Add install prompt (PWA) and manifest\n- Add update notification when new version is available\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/public/manifest.json` — PWA manifest with app name, icons, theme color\n- `frontend/public/icons/` — App icons at 192x192 and 512x512\n- `frontend/src/registerSW.ts` — service worker registration with update handling\n- `frontend/src/components/UpdatePrompt.tsx` — \"New version available\" notification when SW updates\n- `frontend/vite.config.ts` — updated with `vite-plugin-pwa` configuration\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- After first visit (online), navigating to the app URL with no network loads the full app UI (not a browser error page)\n- The app shell (HTML, CSS, JS) is served from the service worker cache\n- All static assets (fonts, icons) are cached and served offline\n- API requests that fail due to network are gracefully handled (no unhandled promise rejections)\n- `manifest.json` is valid — Chrome DevTools > Application > Manifest shows no errors\n- On mobile Chrome/Safari, the \"Add to Home Screen\" prompt is available\n- When a new version is deployed and the user revisits, a non-intrusive \"Update available — click to refresh\" prompt appears\n- The service worker does not cache API responses (IndexedDB handles that from Sprint 5)\n- Lighthouse PWA audit scores 90+ on installability and offline capability\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `vite-plugin-pwa` with `workbox` for service worker generation — avoid hand-rolling cache logic\n- Cache strategy: precache the app shell (index.html, JS bundles, CSS); use `NetworkOnly` for API routes\n- Service worker update flow: `skipWaiting()` on user confirmation, then `clients.claim()` and reload\n- Generate icons from a single SVG source\n- The manifest `start_url` should be `/` and `display` should be `standalone`\n- Test offline behavior in Chrome DevTools > Network > Offline checkbox\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 7: Conflict Resolution & Sync Robustness\n\n### Scope\n- Implement last-write-wins conflict resolution with server timestamps\n- Add a batch sync endpoint for efficiency\n- Handle edge cases: duplicate creates, out-of-order operations, server errors during sync\n- Add sync retry with exponential backoff\n- Backend versioning for optimistic concurrency\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/routes/sync.py` — `POST /api/sync` batch endpoint accepting an array of operations\n- `backend/models.py` — uses `version` field on todos for optimistic concurrency\n- `frontend/src/sync/conflictResolver.ts` — conflict detection and resolution logic\n- `frontend/src/sync/retryStrategy.ts` — exponential backoff with jitter for failed syncs\n- Updated `syncEngine.ts` — uses batch sync and handles conflict responses\n- `backend/tests/test_sync.py` — tests for sync and conflict scenarios\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `POST /api/sync` accepts `{\"operations\": [...]}` and returns `{\"results\": [...], \"server_state\": [...]}`\n- When the same todo is edited on two devices (simulated by direct API call + offline edit), the later timestamp wins\n- If an offline delete conflicts with an online edit, the delete wins (delete is authoritative)\n- If an offline create has an ID that already exists on the server, the server returns the existing item (idempotent)\n- After conflict resolution, the client's IndexedDB matches the server's authoritative state\n- Sync retries with exponential backoff: first retry at ~1s, second at ~2s, third at ~4s, max 30s\n- After 5 consecutive sync failures, the sync indicator shows \"Sync error — tap to retry\"\n- Server returns 409 with conflict details when a `version` mismatch is detected on update\n- The `version` field increments on every successful update\n- Each sync result includes `{\"id\": \"...\", \"status\": \"ok\"|\"conflict\"|\"error\", \"data\": {...}}`\n- Backend sync endpoint processes operations in a single database transaction\n- Running `cd backend && python -m pytest tests/test_sync.py` passes with all conflict scenarios covered\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Last-write-wins uses `updated_at` timestamps; the server is the authority on time\n- Batch sync endpoint processes operations transactionally — all succeed or all fail with details\n- Version field enables optimistic concurrency: client sends version with updates, server rejects stale versions\n- Exponential backoff formula: `min(base * 2^attempt + jitter, maxDelay)` where jitter is random 0-500ms\n- Conflict response format: `{\"id\": \"...\", \"status\": \"conflict\", \"server_version\": {...}, \"resolution\": \"server_wins\"}`\n- Sync queue replay: process in FIFO order; a failure for one todo doesn't block other todos\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 8: Visual Polish, Accessibility & Dark Mode\n\n### Scope\n- Implement a dark mode with system preference detection and manual toggle\n- Ensure full WCAG 2.1 AA accessibility compliance\n- Add contextual animations and visual polish\n- Implement responsive design from 320px to 1440px+\n- Add subtle branding and personality to the app\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` — theme detection and toggle with localStorage persistence\n- `frontend/src/components/ThemeToggle.tsx` — light/dark mode switch with sun/moon icon\n- `frontend/src/styles/tokens.css` — updated design token system with light and dark variants\n- Updated all components with ARIA attributes, roles, and keyboard handling\n- `frontend/src/components/FocusTrap.tsx` — focus trap for modals/dialogs\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useListNavigation.ts` — arrow key navigation for the todo list\n- Updated responsive styles for all breakpoints\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- App defaults to the system color scheme (`prefers-color-scheme` media query)\n- User can toggle between light and dark mode via a sun/moon icon button in the header\n- Theme preference persists in localStorage — reloading the page preserves the choice\n- Dark mode has sufficient contrast ratios (4.5:1 for text, 3:1 for UI elements) — verifiable with Chrome DevTools\n- Dark mode feels intentional — distinct palette, not just inverted colors\n- All interactive elements are reachable via keyboard (Tab, Shift+Tab)\n- All interactive elements have visible focus indicators (not just outline: none)\n- Screen reader announces: todo items with their state, filter changes, sync status, error messages\n- Focus is trapped inside modals; Escape closes and returns focus to trigger element\n- At 320px viewport width, the app is fully usable — no horizontal scrolling, no overlapping elements\n- On mobile (< 640px): larger touch targets (min 44x44px), drag handle area is wider\n- At 1440px+, the app is centered with comfortable max-width and doesn't look stretched\n- Empty state, error state, and loading state all look intentionally designed (not afterthoughts)\n- Color is never the sole indicator of state (completed todos have both color change AND strikethrough/icon)\n- Completing a todo plays a satisfying checkmark draw animation\n- All animations respect `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce`\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use CSS custom properties for all colors, switching values in a `[data-theme=\"dark\"]` selector on `<html>`\n- Theme toggle should update `<html>` attribute AND localStorage in a single action\n- Use `aria-live=\"polite\"` for sync indicator and filter count changes\n- Use `role=\"list\"` and `role=\"listitem\"` for the todo list for proper semantics\n- Test with VoiceOver (macOS) or NVDA (Windows) for screen reader compatibility\n- Use `focus-visible` for focus indicators that only show on keyboard navigation\n- Store theme in localStorage key `theme` with values `light`, `dark`, `system`\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 9: Testing & Performance\n\n### Scope\n- Write comprehensive tests: unit tests for backend and frontend, integration tests for API, E2E tests for critical flows\n- Optimize bundle size and rendering performance\n- Add performance monitoring and Lighthouse optimization\n- Ensure 80%+ test coverage across the codebase\n- Add React error boundaries for graceful failure recovery\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/tests/` — expanded pytest test suite: `test_todos.py`, `test_sync.py`, `test_validation.py`\n- `frontend/src/__tests__/` — Vitest unit tests for store, sync engine, and components\n- `frontend/e2e/` — Playwright E2E tests for critical user flows\n- `frontend/e2e/todo-crud.spec.ts` — CRUD flow tests\n- `frontend/e2e/drag-reorder.spec.ts` — drag-and-drop tests\n- `frontend/e2e/offline-sync.spec.ts` — offline mode and sync tests\n- `frontend/e2e/filters-search.spec.ts` — filter and search tests\n- `frontend/src/components/ErrorBoundary.tsx` — error boundary with recovery UI\n- `frontend/vite.config.ts` — optimized build configuration (code splitting, tree shaking)\n- `backend/conftest.py` — test fixtures with in-memory SQLite database\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `cd backend && python -m pytest --cov` passes with 80%+ line coverage\n- Backend tests cover: CRUD operations, input validation (empty title, long title, invalid ID), reorder logic, batch sync, conflict resolution\n- `cd frontend && npm run test` runs all frontend unit tests via Vitest and passes with 80%+ coverage\n- Frontend tests cover: Zustand store actions, sync engine queue/replay logic, API client error handling, component rendering\n- `cd frontend && npx playwright test` runs E2E tests in headless Chromium and passes\n- E2E tests cover: add a todo, edit a todo, complete a todo, delete a todo, reorder todos, filter todos, keyboard navigation\n- E2E tests produce screenshots on failure\n- Production build (`npm run build`) produces a bundle under 200KB gzipped (excluding icons)\n- Lighthouse performance score is 90+ on a production build\n- If a component throws during render, error boundary shows \"Something went wrong\" with a \"Try again\" button\n- No React re-renders on typing in the add input (verified by test)\n- API response times are under 50ms for all CRUD operations\n- All E2E tests use `page.context().setOffline(true)` for offline scenarios\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `httpx.AsyncClient` with `TestClient` for FastAPI testing — no real server needed\n- Use in-memory SQLite (`:memory:`) for test isolation — each test gets a fresh database\n- Vitest with `@testing-library/react` and `@testing-library/user-event` for component tests; mock the API layer\n- Playwright config: `webServer` option to auto-start both frontend and backend during E2E runs\n- Code split the DnD library — it's only needed when interacting with the list\n- Use `React.lazy` for the keyboard shortcuts modal\n- Error boundary: wrap app root and todo list separately for granular recovery\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 10: Deployment Configuration & Final Integration\n\n### Scope\n- Create Docker Compose setup for running the full stack locally\n- Add a production build pipeline with environment configuration\n- Final integration testing of all features working together\n- Add a README with setup instructions, architecture overview, and development guide\n- Polish any remaining rough edges from previous sprints\n- Add structured logging to the backend\n\n### Deliverables\n- `Dockerfile` for backend (multi-stage: builder + slim runtime)\n- `frontend/Dockerfile` for frontend (multi-stage: build + nginx)\n- `docker-compose.yml` — runs both services with proper networking\n- `.env.example` — d