            "content": "# Todo App — Build Plan\n\n## Product Vision\n\nThis is not just another todo app — it's a thoughtfully crafted productivity tool that feels fast, reliable, and delightful to use regardless of network conditions. The app combines a modern React frontend with a FastAPI backend and SQLite persistence, but its distinguishing quality is its offline-first architecture: every interaction is instant because the local state is the source of truth, with seamless background synchronization when connectivity returns.\n\nThe user experience prioritizes direct manipulation — drag-to-reorder, inline editing, smooth animations on every state change — so the app feels like a native desktop tool rather than a web page. Error states are handled gracefully with optimistic updates and conflict resolution that never loses user data. The design language is minimal but polished, with attention to typography, spacing, and micro-interactions that reward careful use.\n\nBeyond core CRUD, the app introduces smart organization features: nested sub-tasks, keyboard-driven workflows, batch operations, and a command palette for power users. The offline mode isn't a degraded fallback — it's the primary experience, with sync happening invisibly in the background. This positions the app as a reference implementation of offline-first architecture with a React + FastAPI stack.\n\n## Technical Architecture\n\n### Frontend (React + Vite + TypeScript)\n\n- **State Management**: Zustand store with immutable update patterns. Local-first: all mutations apply to the local store immediately, then enqueue sync operations.\n- **Offline Storage**: IndexedDB via Dexie.js for structured local persistence. Service Worker for asset caching and offline shell.\n- **Sync Engine**: Custom sync queue that batches pending mutations, sends them to the backend when online, and reconciles conflicts using last-write-wins with vector clocks per item.\n- **UI Layer**: Component library built from scratch (no heavy UI framework) — custom drag-and-drop, inline editors, animated transitions via CSS transitions and Framer Motion.\n- **Routing**: React Router for potential multi-view navigation (inbox, completed, search).\n\n### Backend (FastAPI + SQLite + Python 3.12+)\n\n- **API Design**: RESTful JSON API with consistent envelope format (`{ data, error, meta }`). Versioned under `/api/v1/`.\n- **Database**: SQLite with WAL mode for concurrent reads. Schema managed via Alembic migrations.\n- **Sync Protocol**: Accepts batched mutation payloads from clients. Returns server-side timestamps and conflict markers. Supports delta sync via `since` parameter.\n- **Validation**: Pydantic v2 models for all request/response schemas with strict validation.\n\n### Offline-First Data Flow\n\n```\nUser Action → Local Store (Zustand) → IndexedDB (Dexie) → Sync Queue\n                                                              ↓\n                                                     [Online?] → FastAPI → SQLite\n                                                              ↓\n                                                     [Offline] → Queue persisted in IndexedDB\n                                                              ↓\n                                                     [Reconnect] → Flush queue → Reconcile\n```\n\n### Project Structure\n\n```\ntodo-app/\n├── frontend/\n│   ├── src/\n│   │   ├── components/       # UI components (TodoItem, TodoList, etc.)\n│   │   ├── stores/           # Zustand stores\n│   │   ├── sync/             # Sync engine, conflict resolution\n│   │   ├── db/               # Dexie.js IndexedDB layer\n│   │   ├── hooks/            # Custom React hooks\n│   │   ├── styles/           # Global styles, design tokens\n│   │   └── types/            # TypeScript type definitions\n│   ├── public/\n│   │   └── sw.js             # Service worker\n│   ├── index.html\n│   ├── vite.config.ts\n│   ├── tsconfig.json\n│   └── package.json\n├── backend/\n│   ├── app/\n│   │   ├── main.py           # FastAPI app entry\n│   │   ├── api/              # Route handlers\n│   │   ├── models/           # Pydantic schemas\n│   │   ├── db/               # SQLite connection, repositories\n│   │   └── sync/             # Sync protocol logic\n│   ├── alembic/              # Database migrations\n│   ├── tests/\n│   ├── pyproject.toml\n│   └── alembic.ini\n└── README.md\n```\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 1: Project Skeleton & Core Backend\n\n### Scope\n- Initialize frontend (Vite + React + TypeScript) and backend (FastAPI + SQLite) projects with full build tooling.\n- Establish database schema and migrations for todos.\n- Implement core CRUD REST API for todo items.\n- Set up dev server with hot reload for both frontend and backend.\n- Create shared TypeScript types and Pydantic models.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/package.json` with Vite, React 18, TypeScript configured\n- `frontend/vite.config.ts` with proxy to backend API\n- `backend/pyproject.toml` with FastAPI, uvicorn, SQLAlchemy, Alembic, pytest\n- `backend/app/main.py` — FastAPI app with CORS middleware\n- `backend/app/db/database.py` — SQLite connection with WAL mode\n- `backend/app/db/repositories/todo_repository.py` — Repository pattern for todos\n- `backend/app/models/todo.py` — Pydantic request/response models\n- `backend/app/api/todos.py` — CRUD endpoints\n- `backend/alembic/versions/001_create_todos.py` — Initial migration\n- `backend/tests/test_todos.py` — API tests for all CRUD operations\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- `npm run dev` starts the frontend on port 5173 without errors\n- `uvicorn app.main:app --reload` starts the backend on port 8000\n- `POST /api/v1/todos` with `{ \"title\": \"Buy milk\" }` returns 201 with the created todo including `id`, `title`, `completed`, `position`, `created_at`, `updated_at`\n- `GET /api/v1/todos` returns 200 with a JSON envelope `{ \"data\": [...], \"error\": null, \"meta\": { \"total\": N } }`\n- `PATCH /api/v1/todos/{id}` with `{ \"title\": \"Buy oat milk\" }` returns 200 with updated todo\n- `DELETE /api/v1/todos/{id}` returns 204 and subsequent GET does not include the deleted item\n- `PATCH /api/v1/todos/{id}` with `{ \"completed\": true }` marks a todo as done\n- All API responses follow the envelope format `{ data, error, meta }`\n- Backend tests pass with `pytest` and cover all CRUD operations\n- Database uses WAL mode (verified by `PRAGMA journal_mode` returning `wal`)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use SQLAlchemy Core (not ORM) for lightweight queries, or SQLAlchemy ORM if preferred — keep it consistent.\n- The `position` field is a float to allow easy reordering (insert between two items by averaging positions).\n- Set up Alembic with `--autogenerate` support for future migrations.\n- Configure CORS to allow `http://localhost:5173` in development.\n- Use `python-dotenv` for configuration management.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 2: Frontend Foundation & Todo List UI\n\n### Scope\n- Build the core React component tree: App shell, TodoList, TodoItem.\n- Implement Zustand store with immutable state management for todos.\n- Connect frontend to backend API with a typed API client.\n- Display todos fetched from the backend, with loading and error states.\n- Implement add, toggle complete, and delete operations from the UI.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/types/todo.ts` — TypeScript interfaces matching backend models\n- `frontend/src/api/client.ts` — Typed fetch wrapper for the backend API\n- `frontend/src/stores/todoStore.ts` — Zustand store with todo state and actions\n- `frontend/src/components/App.tsx` — App shell with header and main content area\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoList.tsx` — Renders list of TodoItem components\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — Single todo with checkbox, title, delete button\n- `frontend/src/components/AddTodo.tsx` — Input field for adding new todos\n- `frontend/src/styles/` — Base styles, CSS custom properties for design tokens\n- `frontend/src/components/EmptyState.tsx` — Friendly empty state when no todos exist\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Opening `http://localhost:5173` shows the todo app with a clean, minimal design\n- Typing \"Buy groceries\" in the input and pressing Enter creates a new todo that appears in the list without a page reload\n- Clicking the checkbox on a todo toggles its completed state, showing a visual strikethrough\n- Clicking the delete button on a todo removes it from the list with no page reload\n- When the backend is returning data, a loading indicator is shown briefly\n- When the API returns an error, a user-friendly error message appears (not a raw error)\n- The empty state shows a friendly message like \"No todos yet — add one above!\"\n- All state updates are immutable (no direct mutation of store state)\n- The design uses a consistent color palette with at least 3 design tokens (background, text, accent)\n- The app is usable on mobile viewports (320px width)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use `fetch` with a thin wrapper, not axios — keep dependencies minimal.\n- Zustand store should use the `immer` middleware for ergonomic immutable updates, or manual spread patterns.\n- API client should handle the envelope format and unwrap `data` for consumers.\n- Use CSS custom properties (not CSS-in-JS) for theming tokens.\n- Optimistic updates: apply changes to the local store first, then sync with the API. Revert on failure.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 3: Inline Editing & Reordering\n\n### Scope\n- Implement inline editing: double-click or tap a todo title to edit it in place.\n- Implement drag-and-drop reordering of todos with smooth animations.\n- Persist new order to the backend via a reorder endpoint.\n- Add keyboard navigation: arrow keys to move between items, Enter to edit, Escape to cancel.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — Enhanced with inline edit mode\n- `frontend/src/components/DragHandle.tsx` — Drag handle indicator for reordering\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useDragReorder.ts` — Custom hook for drag-and-drop reorder logic\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useKeyboardNav.ts` — Keyboard navigation hook\n- `backend/app/api/todos.py` — New `PATCH /api/v1/todos/reorder` endpoint\n- `backend/tests/test_reorder.py` — Tests for reorder endpoint\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Double-clicking a todo title transforms it into an editable text input pre-filled with the current title\n- Pressing Enter while editing saves the new title and exits edit mode\n- Pressing Escape while editing discards changes and exits edit mode\n- Clicking outside the edit input saves the changes (blur-to-save)\n- Dragging a todo by its handle moves it to a new position in the list with a smooth animation (no jumping)\n- After reordering, refreshing the page shows todos in the new order (persisted to backend)\n- `PATCH /api/v1/todos/reorder` with `{ \"id\": \"abc\", \"after_id\": \"def\" }` updates positions correctly\n- Arrow keys (Up/Down) move focus between todo items with a visible focus indicator\n- Enter key on a focused todo enters edit mode\n- Escape key on a focused todo deselects it\n- Empty title (whitespace only) is rejected with a visual error — the todo is not saved\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Implement drag-and-drop using native HTML Drag and Drop API or Pointer Events — avoid heavy libraries like react-beautiful-dnd.\n- Reorder positions using fractional indexing: when inserting between position 1.0 and 2.0, assign 1.5. Periodically re-normalize positions on the backend.\n- Use CSS `transition` for reorder animations, not JS animation libraries.\n- The inline editor should auto-focus and select all text on activation.\n- Keyboard navigation should follow WAI-ARIA listbox patterns for accessibility.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 4: Offline Storage with IndexedDB\n\n### Scope\n- Integrate Dexie.js for IndexedDB-backed local persistence.\n- Mirror the Zustand store to IndexedDB so todos survive page refreshes without the backend.\n- Implement a persistence layer that loads from IndexedDB on startup and writes on every change.\n- Add online/offline status detection and display.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/db/dexie.ts` — Dexie database schema and initialization\n- `frontend/src/db/todoTable.ts` — Typed Dexie table operations for todos\n- `frontend/src/stores/todoStore.ts` — Enhanced to hydrate from IndexedDB on load\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useOnlineStatus.ts` — Hook that tracks navigator.onLine and fires on change\n- `frontend/src/components/OfflineBanner.tsx` — Visual indicator when offline\n- `frontend/src/sync/persistMiddleware.ts` — Zustand middleware that persists every state change to IndexedDB\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Adding a todo while online, then refreshing the page, shows the todo immediately from IndexedDB before the API responds\n- Toggling airplane mode (or throttling to offline in DevTools) shows an \"Offline\" banner at the top of the app\n- Adding a todo while offline creates it in IndexedDB and shows it in the UI instantly\n- Editing a todo while offline saves the change locally and it persists across page refreshes\n- Deleting a todo while offline removes it locally and it stays deleted after refresh\n- Reconnecting to the network hides the \"Offline\" banner\n- IndexedDB contains a `todos` table with the same schema as the backend model\n- The app loads and is fully interactive within 200ms when offline (no network requests needed)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Dexie.js v4 supports live queries — consider using `useLiveQuery` for reactive IndexedDB reads.\n- The persist middleware should debounce writes to IndexedDB (batch within 100ms) to avoid excessive I/O.\n- IndexedDB hydration should happen before the first render — use a loading gate in the App component.\n- Store a `lastSyncedAt` timestamp in IndexedDB to support delta sync later.\n- Handle the case where IndexedDB is unavailable (private browsing in some browsers) — fall back to memory-only.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 5: Sync Engine & Conflict Resolution\n\n### Scope\n- Build a sync queue that records mutations while offline and flushes them when connectivity returns.\n- Implement the backend sync endpoint that accepts batched mutations.\n- Handle conflicts using last-write-wins with timestamps.\n- Add retry logic with exponential backoff for failed syncs.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncQueue.ts` — Persistent queue of pending mutations in IndexedDB\n- `frontend/src/sync/syncEngine.ts` — Engine that flushes the queue when online, handles retries\n- `frontend/src/sync/conflictResolver.ts` — Conflict resolution logic (last-write-wins)\n- `backend/app/api/sync.py` — `POST /api/v1/sync` endpoint accepting batched mutations\n- `backend/app/sync/processor.py` — Server-side sync processing and conflict detection\n- `backend/tests/test_sync.py` — Sync endpoint tests including conflict scenarios\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useSyncStatus.ts` — Hook exposing sync state (synced, pending, syncing, error)\n- `frontend/src/components/SyncIndicator.tsx` — Visual sync status indicator\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Adding 3 todos offline, then reconnecting, syncs all 3 to the backend within 5 seconds\n- The sync indicator shows \"Syncing...\" during flush and \"Synced\" when complete\n- If the backend is down, sync retries with exponential backoff (1s, 2s, 4s, up to 30s max)\n- `POST /api/v1/sync` with `{ \"mutations\": [{ \"type\": \"create\", \"data\": {...}, \"timestamp\": \"...\" }, ...] }` returns 200 with results per mutation\n- Editing the same todo on two clients — client A sets title to \"A\", client B sets title to \"B\" with a later timestamp — results in \"B\" winning and both clients converging\n- Deleting a todo offline and editing it on another client results in the delete winning (delete beats edit)\n- The pending mutation count is shown in the sync indicator (e.g., \"3 changes pending\")\n- Mutations are applied in causal order (create before update, update before delete)\n- A failed individual mutation in a batch does not block other mutations from syncing\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Each mutation in the queue should include: `id`, `type` (create/update/delete), `data`, `timestamp`, `retryCount`.\n- Use `navigator.onLine` + periodic health check pings to detect connectivity more reliably.\n- The sync endpoint should be idempotent — replaying the same mutation (by mutation ID) should not create duplicates.\n- Consider using a `version` or `updated_at` field on todos for optimistic concurrency control.\n- Batch size limit: max 50 mutations per sync request to avoid timeouts.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 6: Service Worker & Full Offline Shell\n\n### Scope\n- Register a Service Worker that caches the app shell (HTML, JS, CSS) for instant offline loading.\n- Implement a cache-first strategy for static assets and network-first for API calls.\n- Add a PWA manifest for installability.\n- Ensure the entire app works end-to-end with zero network connectivity.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/public/sw.js` — Service Worker with caching strategies\n- `frontend/public/manifest.json` — PWA manifest with icons and theme\n- `frontend/src/sw-register.ts` — Service Worker registration with update detection\n- `frontend/public/icons/` — App icons in multiple sizes (192x192, 512x512)\n- `frontend/src/components/UpdateBanner.tsx` — \"New version available\" banner when SW updates\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- After first load, turning off the network and refreshing the page loads the full app instantly (no \"dinosaur\" page)\n- The browser's \"Install App\" prompt appears (or the install button is available in the address bar)\n- Static assets (JS, CSS, images) are served from the Service Worker cache when offline\n- API requests that fail due to being offline are handled gracefully (no uncaught errors in console)\n- When a new version of the app is deployed, users see a \"New version available — click to update\" banner\n- Clicking the update banner activates the new Service Worker and refreshes the page\n- The app's Lighthouse PWA score is 90+ (installable, fast, works offline)\n- The manifest correctly specifies the app name, colors, and icons\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Use Workbox (via `vite-plugin-pwa`) for Service Worker generation — don't hand-write caching logic.\n- Cache strategy: precache the app shell (HTML + JS + CSS), runtime cache API responses with network-first + fallback.\n- The SW should skip waiting on update if the user clicks the update banner.\n- Generate icons from a single SVG source using a build script.\n- Test offline behavior in Chrome DevTools Application > Service Workers > Offline checkbox.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 7: Sub-tasks & Nested Todos\n\n### Scope\n- Extend the data model to support sub-tasks (parent-child relationships).\n- Allow users to indent/outdent todos to create hierarchy.\n- Render nested todos with visual indentation and collapse/expand.\n- Sub-tasks inherit completion state from parent (completing parent completes children).\n\n### Deliverables\n- `backend/alembic/versions/002_add_parent_id.py` — Migration adding `parent_id` column\n- `backend/app/models/todo.py` — Updated models with `parent_id` and `children` fields\n- `backend/app/db/repositories/todo_repository.py` — Updated queries for hierarchical data\n- `frontend/src/components/TodoItem.tsx` — Enhanced with indent level, collapse toggle\n- `frontend/src/components/SubTaskList.tsx` — Renders children of a todo\n- `frontend/src/stores/todoStore.ts` — Tree structure support with flatten/unflatten utilities\n- `backend/tests/test_subtasks.py` — Tests for nested todo operations\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Pressing Tab on a focused todo indents it, making it a child of the todo above\n- Pressing Shift+Tab on a sub-task outdents it back to the parent level\n- Sub-tasks are visually indented with a subtle left border or connector line\n- A parent todo with children shows a collapse/expand chevron\n- Clicking the chevron hides/shows children with a smooth animation\n- Completing a parent todo marks all its children as completed\n- Uncompleting a parent todo uncompletes all its children\n- Deleting a parent todo also deletes all its children (cascade)\n- `GET /api/v1/todos` returns todos with a `children` array (tree structure) or a flat list with `parent_id`\n- Sub-tasks support the same operations as top-level todos: edit, reorder, drag-and-drop within their parent\n- Maximum nesting depth is 3 levels (enforced in UI and API)\n\n### Technical Notes\n- Store todos flat in the database with `parent_id` foreign key. Build tree structure in the API response or on the client.\n- Tab/Shift+Tab for indent/outdent follows the same pattern as Notion or Workflowy.\n- Collapse state should be stored locally (IndexedDB) — it's a UI preference, not synced.\n- Drag-and-drop within nested structures is complex — restrict to moving within the same parent for now, enable cross-parent moves as a stretch goal.\n- Consider a `path` materialized field (e.g., `/root/parent/child`) for efficient subtree queries.\n\n---\n\n## Sprint 8: Command Palette & Keyboard Power Features\n\n### Scope\n- Implement a command palette (Cmd+K / Ctrl+K) for quick actions.\n- Add batch operations: select multiple todos, bulk complete, bulk delete.\n- Implement search/filter within the command palette.\n- Add keyboard shortcuts for all common operations.\n\n### Deliverables\n- `frontend/src/components/CommandPalette.tsx` — Modal command palette with fuzzy search\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useCommandPalette.ts` — Command registration and execution\n- `frontend/src/hooks/useKeyboardShortcuts.ts` — Global keyboard shortcut handler\n- `frontend/src/components/BatchBar.tsx` — Batch action toolbar (appears when items are selected)\n- `frontend/src/components/ShortcutHelp.tsx` — Keyboard shortcut reference (? to open)\n- `frontend/src/stores/selectionStore.ts` — Multi-select state management\n\n### Acceptance Criteria\n- Pressing Cmd+K (Mac) or Ctrl+K (Windows) opens a centered modal with